WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.040 --> 00:00:04.730
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, DC.

00:00:20.040 --> 00:00:21.340
&gt;&gt; Ralph Ehrenberg:
I am Ralph Ehrenberg,

00:00:21.340 --> 00:00:23.200
chief of the geography
and map division.

00:00:23.200 --> 00:00:27.490
It is my great pleasure to welcome
you here to the Library today

00:00:27.490 --> 00:00:31.930
for our two-day conference on Facts
or Fictions, Debating the Mysteries

00:00:31.930 --> 00:00:34.930
of Early Modern Science
and Cartography,

00:00:34.930 --> 00:00:36.650
which is being sponsored
by the Jay I.

00:00:36.650 --> 00:00:43.560
Kislak Family Foundation and the
Virginia Gray Family Memorial Fund.

00:00:43.560 --> 00:00:45.920
This conference was
planned and organized

00:00:45.920 --> 00:00:48.940
by Dr. John Hessler,
curator of the Jay I.

00:00:48.940 --> 00:00:53.290
Kislak collection of archaeology
and history of the early Americas

00:00:53.290 --> 00:00:57.480
at the Library of Congress,
and John is also the geography

00:00:57.480 --> 00:01:00.100
and map division specialist
in modern cartography

00:01:00.100 --> 00:01:03.520
and geographic information systems.

00:01:03.520 --> 00:01:08.610
The subtitle of our conference is
a celebration of 500th anniversary

00:01:08.610 --> 00:01:12.960
of Waldseemuller's
1516 Carta Marina.

00:01:12.960 --> 00:01:16.660 position:56%
I'd like to comment briefly on the
Library's acquisition of this chart,

00:01:16.660 --> 00:01:20.580
one of the great masterpieces
of Renaissance mapping.

00:01:20.580 --> 00:01:24.180
Shortly after its publication,
our copy of this map was acquired

00:01:24.180 --> 00:01:28.070
by Johann Schoner [phonetic],
a noted Nuremberg mathematician

00:01:28.070 --> 00:01:32.450
and geographer, who bound
it together with a number

00:01:32.450 --> 00:01:37.600
of globe gores drawn by him,
the earliest printed star chart

00:01:37.600 --> 00:01:41.500
of the southern hemisphere
engraved by Albrecht Durer,

00:01:41.500 --> 00:01:47.670 position:56%
and Waldseemuller's other famous map
is 1507 Universalis Cosmographia,

00:01:47.670 --> 00:01:50.370
the map that named America.

00:01:50.370 --> 00:01:53.780
With the recent acquisition
of Durer's star chart,

00:01:53.780 --> 00:01:56.530
the Library of Congress has
now brought back together all

00:01:56.530 --> 00:01:59.530
of the maps and charts that
were originally contained

00:01:59.530 --> 00:02:04.370
in Schoner's bound portfolio now
known as the Schoner's [inaudible].

00:02:05.420 --> 00:02:08.030
This portfolio was
unknown to the wider world

00:02:08.030 --> 00:02:13.900 position:56%
for some 350 years although
Washington Irving's research in 1828

00:02:13.900 --> 00:02:20.150
on the origin of the name America
cited Waldseemuller's 1507 map.

00:02:20.150 --> 00:02:24.500
German geographer Alexander
von Humboldt later alluded

00:02:24.500 --> 00:02:29.140
to Irving's work, stimulating
a further search for the map.

00:02:29.140 --> 00:02:32.000
No copies were found,
however, until 1901,

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:36.590
when the Austrian Jesuit scholar,
Josef Fischer, who we'll hear more

00:02:36.590 --> 00:02:39.810
about shortly, located
this map while searching

00:02:39.810 --> 00:02:47.640
for material relating to the early
Norse voyages to North America.

00:02:47.640 --> 00:02:51.360
It was found in the
Waldburg-Wolfegg family castle

00:02:51.360 --> 00:02:53.640
in south central Germany.

00:02:53.640 --> 00:02:58.130
Fortunately, this family
had provided a safe haven

00:02:58.130 --> 00:03:02.310
through three centuries of numerous
wars and political upheavals.

00:03:02.310 --> 00:03:08.430
As early as 1912, Prince
Johannes Waldburg-Wolfegg offered

00:03:08.430 --> 00:03:12.250
Waldseemuller's 1507 map
to the Library of Congress

00:03:12.250 --> 00:03:15.330
where he believed it would be more
readily available for research

00:03:15.330 --> 00:03:21.120 position:56%
on display, but limited resources
prevented its purchase at that time.

00:03:21.120 --> 00:03:25.000
In 1977, the chief of the
geography division at that time,

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:28.730
Walter W. Ristow, viewed
the Schoner portfolio

00:03:28.730 --> 00:03:30.030
at the castle during a visit

00:03:30.030 --> 00:03:34.770
with Count Maxwell
Wilbrod [phonetic] Walburg.

00:03:34.770 --> 00:03:39.050
Six years later, the
Schoner portfolio was loaned

00:03:39.050 --> 00:03:42.430
to the Smithsonian Institution's
National Museum of American History

00:03:42.430 --> 00:03:46.260
for exhibition focusing
on the naming of America.

00:03:46.260 --> 00:03:50.800
The centerpiece of this exhibition
was Waldseemuller's 1507 map

00:03:50.800 --> 00:03:52.700
with one sheet of the map displayed

00:03:52.700 --> 00:03:56.490
at a time most frequently the one
contained in the name America.

00:03:56.490 --> 00:04:00.730
The Schoner portfolio made a return
visit to the nation's capital

00:04:00.730 --> 00:04:05.950
in 1992 during the Columbus
quincentenary celebration.

00:04:05.950 --> 00:04:09.700
On that occasion, the Folger
Shakespeare Library's conservation

00:04:09.700 --> 00:04:14.850
staff removed the 12 woodcut
map plates of the 1507 map

00:04:14.850 --> 00:04:18.860
from its portfolio, binding and
reassembling them as a wall map

00:04:18.860 --> 00:04:23.650
for the first time for display
in the National Gallery of Art.

00:04:23.650 --> 00:04:27.570
Former Librarian of Congress James
Billington began discussing during

00:04:27.570 --> 00:04:30.950
this period with Count
Johannes Walburg

00:04:30.950 --> 00:04:33.850
about acquiring the 1507 map.

00:04:33.850 --> 00:04:39.250
It was purchased in 2003 with a $5
million appropriation from Congress

00:04:39.250 --> 00:04:41.220
and matching funds
generously donated

00:04:41.220 --> 00:04:44.480
by George Topolowski
[phonetic], Virginia Gray,

00:04:44.480 --> 00:04:46.200
Gerald Landfest [phonetic],
David Kauf [phonetic],

00:04:46.200 --> 00:04:48.490
and the Discovery Channel.

00:04:48.490 --> 00:04:51.890
German Chancellor Angela Merkel
formally transferred this treasure

00:04:51.890 --> 00:04:54.990
to the American people
in an official ceremony

00:04:54.990 --> 00:04:59.360
in the Thomas Jefferson
building in 2007.

00:04:59.360 --> 00:05:08.330
Waldseemuller's 1516 Carta Marina,
the subject of our work today,

00:05:08.330 --> 00:05:09.810
was later purchased by Jay I.

00:05:09.810 --> 00:05:14.140
Kislak along with the rest
of Schoner's portfolio,

00:05:14.140 --> 00:05:16.320
which included Schoner's
important celestial

00:05:16.320 --> 00:05:18.550
and terrestrial globe gores.

00:05:18.550 --> 00:05:23.980
Mr. Kislak then arranged for
the donation of the Carta Marina

00:05:23.980 --> 00:05:26.080
and the globe gores to the
Library of Congress along

00:05:26.080 --> 00:05:28.700
with his monumental
American Collection.

00:05:28.700 --> 00:05:36.130 position:56%
Durer's star chart was acquired late
last year with appropriated funds,

00:05:36.130 --> 00:05:39.710
which added the final piece that
compromised Schoner's [inaudible].

00:05:39.710 --> 00:05:45.860
Thanks to the dedication and the
public spirit of these donors,

00:05:45.860 --> 00:05:48.930
Schoner's portfolio with
Waldseemuller's two master maps,

00:05:48.930 --> 00:05:52.940
Schoner's globe gores, and Durer's
star chart will remain together,

00:05:52.940 --> 00:05:58.700
available for future generations
for examination and study.

00:05:58.700 --> 00:06:02.420
Waldseemuller's 1507 map is on
permanent display in this bleeding

00:06:02.420 --> 00:06:06.990
in the second floor gallery
along with Durer's star chart.

00:06:06.990 --> 00:06:11.780
The Schoner portfolio with the 1516
map will be on display tomorrow

00:06:11.780 --> 00:06:15.620
in the geography and map division,
which is located in the basement

00:06:15.620 --> 00:06:19.180
of the Madison building across
the street and will be on display

00:06:19.180 --> 00:06:23.120
from one to three in the afternoon
along with other treasures

00:06:23.120 --> 00:06:26.360
from the map division ranging from
Porterlain [phonetic] charts dating

00:06:26.360 --> 00:06:29.920
from the 13th century to maps

00:06:29.920 --> 00:06:33.190
by George Washington
and Lewis and Clark.

00:06:33.190 --> 00:06:36.850 position:56%
For those of you who aren't familiar
with the geography and map division,

00:06:36.850 --> 00:06:38.610
the division holds
the world's largest

00:06:38.610 --> 00:06:41.310
and most comprehensive
map collection,

00:06:41.310 --> 00:06:46.870
numbering some 5-1/2 million
maps and 80,000 atlases.

00:06:46.870 --> 00:06:51.200
We are open to the public for
research from Monday through Friday

00:06:51.200 --> 00:06:55.900
from 8:30 in the morning
until 5 in the afternoon.

00:06:55.900 --> 00:07:00.020
Established in 1897 as the
Hall of Maps to serve Congress

00:07:00.020 --> 00:07:04.080
and federal agencies, the geography
and map division today functions

00:07:04.080 --> 00:07:06.550
as a national map library.

00:07:06.550 --> 00:07:09.230
It's primary responsibility
is developing the Library's

00:07:09.230 --> 00:07:11.640
cartographic collections.

00:07:11.640 --> 00:07:15.280
An average of some 40,000
items are acquired yearly

00:07:15.280 --> 00:07:18.620
through government deposits,
transfers of superseded maps

00:07:18.620 --> 00:07:22.920
from federal libraries,
copyright deposits, domestic

00:07:22.920 --> 00:07:26.960
and international exchanges,
purchases, and gifts.

00:07:26.960 --> 00:07:30.660
These range from rare globes and
maps to geospatial data sets.

00:07:30.660 --> 00:07:35.470 position:56%
Our cartographic collection is dated
as I said from the 13th century

00:07:35.470 --> 00:07:39.020
and covers virtually all
countries and subjects.

00:07:39.020 --> 00:07:42.670
While many of the current items
are acquired through exchange

00:07:42.670 --> 00:07:46.700
and deposits, the division relies
heavily on donors to assist

00:07:46.700 --> 00:07:50.250
in the acquisition of rare
maps and unique collections.

00:07:50.250 --> 00:07:53.630
In 1995, we established
a public support group,

00:07:53.630 --> 00:07:57.210
the Philip Lee Phillips Map
Society of the Library of Congress

00:07:57.210 --> 00:08:01.240
for those persons who wished to
support the work of the division.

00:08:01.240 --> 00:08:03.510
The Phillips Society
issues four newsletters

00:08:03.510 --> 00:08:06.170
and two occasional papers yearly.

00:08:06.170 --> 00:08:09.290 position:56%
A copy of our most recent newsletter
is available at the foyer,

00:08:09.290 --> 00:08:13.100
and I hope these were passed
out to you when you came in.

00:08:13.100 --> 00:08:16.580
If you wish to add your name to our
mailing list, please contact any

00:08:16.580 --> 00:08:19.560
of our staff members
who are in the foyer.

00:08:19.560 --> 00:08:24.830 position:56%
And now it's my pleasure to turn
the podium over to Dr. John Hessler,

00:08:24.830 --> 00:08:28.510
who will begin a formal
program today.

00:08:28.510 --> 00:08:36.040
[ Applause ]

00:08:36.040 --> 00:08:37.920
&gt;&gt; John Hessler: Well, I want
to extend the same welcome

00:08:37.920 --> 00:08:39.280
that Ralph did to everyone.

00:08:39.280 --> 00:08:41.760
Welcome to the Library of Congress.

00:08:41.760 --> 00:08:44.160
We've got kind of a
two-part program today.

00:08:44.160 --> 00:08:48.870
The first part has got a title
called Facts or Fictions,

00:08:48.870 --> 00:08:52.450
the Mysteries of Renaissance
and early cartography.

00:08:52.450 --> 00:08:56.330
Now, the reason we kind of
paired these two things together,

00:08:56.330 --> 00:09:01.450
an afternoon on the 1516
Carta Marina and the mysteries

00:09:01.450 --> 00:09:03.800
of other maps of the
period is simply

00:09:03.800 --> 00:09:07.580
because the Waldseemuller maps are
also a rather large cartographic

00:09:07.580 --> 00:09:11.270
mystery, and so we thought we
would put in one room a number

00:09:11.270 --> 00:09:15.560
of scholars who've been working on
some of these difficult problems

00:09:15.560 --> 00:09:17.440
in the history of cartography,

00:09:17.440 --> 00:09:23.350
everything from Marco Polo maps all
the way to the 1516 Carta Marina,

00:09:23.350 --> 00:09:26.320
which I believe Chet is going to
actually solve all the problems

00:09:26.320 --> 00:09:29.500
about today, so he's
been working on it.

00:09:29.500 --> 00:09:32.140
One thing I want to
do before we begin

00:09:32.140 --> 00:09:34.980
and before I introduce our
first speaker is I want

00:09:34.980 --> 00:09:40.980
to thank Ralph Ehrenberg for his
service to the Library of Congress

00:09:40.980 --> 00:09:43.590
as chief of the geography
and map division.

00:09:43.590 --> 00:09:48.380
Ralph will be retiring sometime
in the next few months after years

00:09:48.380 --> 00:09:51.120
and years of service
to this institution

00:09:51.120 --> 00:09:54.920
to the national archives
and to this discipline.

00:09:54.920 --> 00:09:59.270
When I was a young student,
when I was an undergraduate,

00:09:59.270 --> 00:10:04.510
I had the opportunity to get a
fellowship at the Vatican Library

00:10:04.510 --> 00:10:07.810
in Rome and actually at the
Vatican Observatory Library,

00:10:07.810 --> 00:10:10.430
and there I met a man whose name
was Pietro Tucci [phonetic].

00:10:10.430 --> 00:10:15.050
Pietro Tucci was a 92-year-old
librarian who believed

00:10:15.050 --> 00:10:21.260
that doing his job, being a rare
book librarian, being a librarian

00:10:21.260 --> 00:10:24.050
of science was one of
the highest callings.

00:10:24.050 --> 00:10:29.040
I appeared on his doorstep
as a very young man of 19.

00:10:29.040 --> 00:10:33.090
He wasn't used to having
19-year-old Americans

00:10:33.090 --> 00:10:35.460
through the Vatican
Observatory Library.

00:10:35.460 --> 00:10:37.430
As a matter of fact, in the
three months I was there,

00:10:37.430 --> 00:10:41.990
I only saw one other human
being besides Pietro Tucci.

00:10:41.990 --> 00:10:45.330
But Pietro Tucci warmed
me and at one point

00:10:45.330 --> 00:10:47.950
in time he called me
back to the stacks.

00:10:47.950 --> 00:10:51.610
And he said, young man, I
want to teach you something.

00:10:51.610 --> 00:10:54.410
I want to show you something
that is more important

00:10:54.410 --> 00:10:55.960
than the work you are doing.

00:10:55.960 --> 00:10:57.260
You're a scholar.

00:10:57.260 --> 00:11:00.070
You're looking at these
books, but let's walk

00:11:00.070 --> 00:11:01.400
down through these stacks.

00:11:01.400 --> 00:11:02.770
And he walked down
through these stacks,

00:11:02.770 --> 00:11:05.700
and occasionally he would pull
a book off the shelf and say,

00:11:05.700 --> 00:11:07.320
this person collected this.

00:11:07.320 --> 00:11:10.590
This was put up here
by this librarian.

00:11:10.590 --> 00:11:14.920
And Pietro Tucci had
come through the war.

00:11:14.920 --> 00:11:18.530
He was an Italian priest of
Polish extraction who had come

00:11:18.530 --> 00:11:23.900
through the war, and Pietro
Tucci wanted me to know that one

00:11:23.900 --> 00:11:27.640
of the most important things
about doing this work is the fact

00:11:27.640 --> 00:11:32.960
that a book standing freely on
a shelf in an open library was

00:11:32.960 --> 00:11:36.120
for him the difference
between lightness and darkness,

00:11:36.120 --> 00:11:38.360
between goodness and evil.

00:11:38.360 --> 00:11:41.980
And he said to me there were
very few people in the world

00:11:41.980 --> 00:11:45.900
who knew this, who practiced this,
who thought this was the purpose

00:11:45.900 --> 00:11:51.020
of a library, that this entire
enterprise was the difference

00:11:51.020 --> 00:11:55.270
between, and he called
it, humanities last stand.

00:11:55.270 --> 00:12:00.050 position:56%
In my 35-year career of doing this
I have met few people who could come

00:12:00.050 --> 00:12:02.800
up to Pietro Tucci's standard.

00:12:02.800 --> 00:12:05.720
One of those people
is Ralph Ehrenberg,

00:12:05.720 --> 00:12:09.880
a man who as I said has dedicated
his life to this institution

00:12:09.880 --> 00:12:12.460
and to the history of
cartography, and I just want

00:12:12.460 --> 00:12:15.510
to congratulate Ralph
on his retirement.

00:12:15.510 --> 00:12:28.040
[ Applause ]

00:12:28.040 --> 00:12:30.510
And with that, I will introduce
our first speaker, Kirsten Seaver.

00:12:30.510 --> 00:12:34.930
Most of the people in this
audience who are involved

00:12:34.930 --> 00:12:38.710 position:56%
in the early history of cartography,
she would need no introduction

00:12:38.710 --> 00:12:43.120
as she is at least to me somewhat
of a legend in this field.

00:12:43.120 --> 00:12:46.330
She is a historian of
the Norse of Greenland,

00:12:46.330 --> 00:12:48.390
the history of the North Atlantic.

00:12:48.390 --> 00:12:50.550
She has written many novels.

00:12:50.550 --> 00:12:51.850
She has traveled widely,

00:12:51.850 --> 00:12:57.100
participated in many documentary
films, and her novelistic talent,

00:12:57.100 --> 00:12:59.770
her talent for writing
novels I think goes deep

00:12:59.770 --> 00:13:02.320
down into her scholarly work.

00:13:02.320 --> 00:13:04.910
She is one of the few people,
I think, who have actively

00:13:04.910 --> 00:13:08.250
and intensely studied the
relationship of Josef Fischer,

00:13:08.250 --> 00:13:12.090
the Norse, and the maps that we
are going to talk about today.

00:13:12.090 --> 00:13:16.510
So without further ado, I would
like to introduce Kirsten Seaver.

00:13:16.510 --> 00:13:26.510
[ Applause ]

00:13:26.510 --> 00:13:39.150
[ Background Noise ]

00:13:39.150 --> 00:13:41.380
&gt;&gt; Kirsten Seaver: Thank you, John,
for that wonderful introduction.

00:13:41.380 --> 00:13:47.910
I was swelling as I was listening
to you, or at least my head was.

00:13:47.910 --> 00:13:51.650
It's a pleasure to be here
tonight, or this morning rather.

00:13:51.650 --> 00:13:56.480
I am confused because I just came
in from California last night,

00:13:56.480 --> 00:14:00.900
and it really is a good cause
because this is a fantastic thing

00:14:00.900 --> 00:14:04.370
to celebrate, having
these maps here.

00:14:04.370 --> 00:14:08.120
Father Josef Fischer, S.J.,
the Arodite [phonetic] German

00:14:08.120 --> 00:14:13.240
and Austrian cartographic
historian, who discovered the 1507

00:14:13.240 --> 00:14:18.860
and 1516 Waldseemuller maps
at Wolfegg castle in 1901,

00:14:18.860 --> 00:14:22.140
some decade later became
the likely author

00:14:22.140 --> 00:14:25.470 position:56%
of Yale's controversial Vinland map.

00:14:25.470 --> 00:14:28.720
And that situation appeared
so incongruous that I want

00:14:28.720 --> 00:14:31.820
to talk this morning
about some of the maps

00:14:31.820 --> 00:14:35.510
and ideas I believe
inspired both events.

00:14:35.510 --> 00:14:47.040
[ Background Noise ]

00:14:47.040 --> 00:14:52.390
Although at the time of his Wolfegg
sojourn, Father Fischer was working

00:14:52.390 --> 00:14:57.270
on his MA thesis for
the-- better, okay?

00:14:57.270 --> 00:14:59.680
Everybody can hear me now?

00:14:59.680 --> 00:15:03.150
At the time of his Wolfegg
sojourn, Father Fischer was working

00:15:03.150 --> 00:15:07.680
on his MA thesis for the
cartographic historian

00:15:07.680 --> 00:15:12.230
and geographer Franz von
Wieser, who had convinced him

00:15:12.230 --> 00:15:14.730
that early cartographic
evidence existed

00:15:14.730 --> 00:15:17.420
for the Norse westward expeditions

00:15:17.420 --> 00:15:21.160
from the recently settled
Greenland colonies

00:15:23.130 --> 00:15:27.480
to the North America
around the year 1000.

00:15:27.480 --> 00:15:30.840
In the aftermath of
the 400th anniversary

00:15:30.840 --> 00:15:34.740
of the Columbian discovery, the
region the Norse called Vinland

00:15:34.740 --> 00:15:40.630
or wine land was the southernmost
of the three American areas

00:15:40.630 --> 00:15:46.110
that the Norse had explored,
and it was the only one

00:15:46.110 --> 00:15:51.330
that interested von
Wieser, Fischer, and others.

00:15:51.330 --> 00:15:56.400
Although Vinland's demographic
extent is in fact unknowable except

00:15:56.400 --> 00:15:58.670
as an area that included
Newfoundland

00:15:58.670 --> 00:16:04.510
and the southern St. Lawrence
[inaudible], Fischer was sure

00:16:04.510 --> 00:16:08.210
that it consisted of Nova Scotia
and Cape Britain combined,

00:16:08.210 --> 00:16:11.960
and he was equally certain that
the climate a thousand years

00:16:11.960 --> 00:16:17.600 position:56%
or so ago was so warm that the Norse
had traveled up both the coasts

00:16:17.600 --> 00:16:21.870
of Greenland and learned their
country's essential shape.

00:16:21.870 --> 00:16:26.800 position:56%
He reasoned that all maps showing
Greenland would also reveal the rest

00:16:26.800 --> 00:16:28.960
of the Norse westward exploits

00:16:28.960 --> 00:16:33.610
as such maps must have a
uniquely German lineage rooted

00:16:33.610 --> 00:16:37.000
in Adam O'Bramen's [phonetic]
11th century references

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:42.350
to the Norse presence in
Iceland, Greenland, and Vinland.

00:16:42.350 --> 00:16:48.340
And he hoped to find further
evidence for his theories

00:16:48.340 --> 00:16:52.950
at Wolfegg castle, a baroque
jewel in Baden-Wurttemberg

00:16:52.950 --> 00:16:57.280
with a magnificent collection
of art objects [inaudible],

00:16:57.280 --> 00:16:59.800
manuscript texts, and maps.

00:16:59.800 --> 00:17:05.320 position:56%
He would not have far to travel, nor
did he need a formal introduction

00:17:05.320 --> 00:17:08.550
because Wolfegg's noble
owners, the Catholic family

00:17:08.550 --> 00:17:12.230
of Altberg [phonetic], Wolfegg
habitually sent their sons

00:17:12.230 --> 00:17:16.850
to be educated at Stella
Matutina, the Catholic school

00:17:16.850 --> 00:17:20.570
in the Austrian border
town of Feldkirch

00:17:20.570 --> 00:17:23.760
where Fischer was teaching
geography and history.

00:17:23.760 --> 00:17:29.830
In 1901, he wrote to the
castle librarian and asked

00:17:29.830 --> 00:17:34.780
if the collections might include
a manuscript map showing Greenland

00:17:34.780 --> 00:17:40.730
as a European peninsula
in the manner of 1482

00:17:40.730 --> 00:17:48.290
and 1486 Olm [phonetic]
geography in the Olm editions.

00:17:48.290 --> 00:17:50.420
And the librarian reported back

00:17:50.420 --> 00:17:53.150
that the search had
yielded a manuscript map

00:17:53.150 --> 00:17:55.580
by Donnes Nicholas
Gamonis [phonetic]

00:17:55.580 --> 00:17:59.290
that might meet Fischer's
requirements.

00:17:59.290 --> 00:18:04.800 position:56%
Fischer soon identified the Nicholas
Gamonis manuscript as the prototype

00:18:04.800 --> 00:18:08.180
of printed maps in the Olm
editions where Greenland

00:18:08.180 --> 00:18:11.930
and the so-called B [phonetic]
reduction is depicted as a large,

00:18:11.930 --> 00:18:18.240
blunt peninsula east of Iceland and
connected to Eurasia above Norway.

00:18:18.240 --> 00:18:23.000
He and von Wieser were already
familiar with the manuscript maps,

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:26.220
which the Benedictine
monk, Nicholas Gamonis,

00:18:26.220 --> 00:18:29.570
had drawn for the so-called
Zamweskee [phonetic] codex

00:18:29.570 --> 00:18:36.240
of circa 1467, and edition
of Ptolemy's Geographia,

00:18:36.240 --> 00:18:38.700
which had strengthened
the two scholars' belief

00:18:38.700 --> 00:18:43.140
that cartographic evidence of
Norse exploration westward must

00:18:43.140 --> 00:18:45.190
have existed.

00:18:45.190 --> 00:18:47.950
The Zamweskee version
shows Greenland

00:18:47.950 --> 00:18:53.640 position:56%
as a pointed peninsula west of
Iceland in the so-called A reduction

00:18:53.640 --> 00:18:57.950
but also linked above Norway
to northwestern Eurasia

00:18:57.950 --> 00:19:03.920
and like the Wolfegg manuscript
indicated a second Greenland

00:19:03.920 --> 00:19:07.760
where Norway meets
Sweden in the north.

00:19:07.760 --> 00:19:11.900
Continuing his searches in the
castle library, Fischer discovered,

00:19:11.900 --> 00:19:16.190
as we have heard, Waldseemuller's
printed world map of 1507

00:19:16.190 --> 00:19:22.540
and the Carta Marina of 1516 in
a bound volume miscellany owned

00:19:22.540 --> 00:19:25.960
by the Nuremberg mathematician
Johannes Schoner.

00:19:25.960 --> 00:19:32.360
As an expert on Ptolemaic maps
of the 15th and 16th centuries,

00:19:32.360 --> 00:19:37.770
Fischer was well equipped to
identify the Waldseemuller maps.

00:19:37.770 --> 00:19:41.620 position:56%
The German academic educate required

00:19:41.620 --> 00:19:45.400
that his thesis advisor
verify the discoveries,

00:19:45.400 --> 00:19:49.960
so in the joint analysis
was published in 1903,

00:19:49.960 --> 00:19:54.330
von Wieser's name joined
Fischer's on the title page.

00:19:54.330 --> 00:19:59.780
In a book that Fischer
published in his own name in 1902

00:19:59.780 --> 00:20:04.830
and which appeared in
English the following year,

00:20:04.830 --> 00:20:08.890 position:56%
he enthusiastically reviewed the
cartographic connections he had made

00:20:08.890 --> 00:20:14.760
at Wolfegg and wrote, this lucky
discovery was remarkable if only

00:20:14.760 --> 00:20:19.270
for its bearing on the discoveries
made by the Norsemen as well

00:20:19.270 --> 00:20:22.150
as on the relation to
the later discoveries

00:20:22.150 --> 00:20:26.070
of Columbus and his successors.

00:20:26.070 --> 00:20:33.370 position:56%
Prior to 1901, the 1520 Petrus
Apianus world map was considered the

00:20:33.370 --> 00:20:38.240
oldest surviving printed
map using the name America.

00:20:38.240 --> 00:20:42.580
Waldseemuller's 1507 map
was known to have existed

00:20:42.580 --> 00:20:46.870
but was believed lost until
Fischer found a surviving example

00:20:46.870 --> 00:20:48.170
at Wolfegg.

00:20:48.170 --> 00:20:54.290
The 1507 map additionally rewarded
him with a prominent Greenland,

00:20:54.290 --> 00:20:59.100 position:56%
shaped and positioned as in the
Wolfegg Nicholas Garmonis manuscript

00:20:59.100 --> 00:21:03.270 position:56%
and the printed Olm maps and linking

00:21:03.270 --> 00:21:07.890
to the Eurasian continent
north of Norway.

00:21:07.890 --> 00:21:11.300
Waldseemuller did not
repeat the name America

00:21:11.300 --> 00:21:17.270
when he made his magnificent
Carta Marina in 1516,

00:21:17.270 --> 00:21:19.950
but like it's 1507 predecessor,

00:21:19.950 --> 00:21:25.420
it featured a large peninsular
Greenland linked to Norway.

00:21:25.420 --> 00:21:28.720
Moreover, like all the
other maps mentioned so far,

00:21:28.720 --> 00:21:33.080
it had a second Greenland where
northern Norway and Sweden met

00:21:33.080 --> 00:21:40.670
and provided similar place names
on the larger Greenland peninsula.

00:21:40.670 --> 00:21:45.710 position:56%
Fischer felt confident that all
these features were directly related

00:21:45.710 --> 00:21:51.050
to the work that the Danish cleric
Claudius Clavus did sometime

00:21:51.050 --> 00:21:55.690
between 1424 and 1427 for inclusion

00:21:55.690 --> 00:22:01.000
with cardinal Gion Feastrus
[phonetic] manuscript copy

00:22:01.000 --> 00:22:06.820
of Ptolemy Geographia, and the
connection is there but not quite

00:22:06.820 --> 00:22:09.390
in the way that Fischer imagined.

00:22:09.390 --> 00:22:13.820
The Clavus map of the north,

00:22:13.820 --> 00:22:17.030 position:56%
which the French scholar Jon Lorr
[phonetic] discovered at [inaudible]

00:22:17.030 --> 00:22:22.190
in 1835 is the first known
cartographic representation

00:22:22.190 --> 00:22:23.490
of Greenland.

00:22:23.490 --> 00:22:26.160
Here it is shown as the east coast

00:22:26.160 --> 00:22:29.570
of a peninsula called
Greenlandia Provincia [phonetic]

00:22:29.570 --> 00:22:30.970
and connected eastward

00:22:30.970 --> 00:22:36.020
to the Eurasian mainland via
the Scandinavian peninsula.

00:22:36.020 --> 00:22:39.210
Because Fischer credited Clavus

00:22:39.210 --> 00:22:42.640
with envisioning a continuous
circumpolar continent,

00:22:42.640 --> 00:22:48.550
he considered the [inaudible] map
the first map to also show America.

00:22:48.550 --> 00:22:55.610
An opinion he developed fully in
1911, unaware that Norse activities

00:22:55.610 --> 00:23:00.230
that far west had long been so
murky in the Danish consciousness

00:23:00.230 --> 00:23:03.480
that Clavus had mistakenly
relegated the Norse

00:23:03.480 --> 00:23:07.590
to the Greenland's east
coast [inaudible] west.

00:23:07.590 --> 00:23:12.520
Ptolemy for his part had never
referred to Greenland by any name.

00:23:12.520 --> 00:23:15.550
Therefore, Blor [phonetic]
considered both the Clavus map

00:23:15.550 --> 00:23:20.060
and a short companion text
worthy of special attention,

00:23:20.060 --> 00:23:23.850
particularly given that both
items were in a hand different

00:23:23.850 --> 00:23:27.230
from that anywhere
else in the codex,

00:23:27.230 --> 00:23:32.960 position:56%
and both employ the Danish letter o/
that is O with a slash rather than O

00:23:32.960 --> 00:23:35.000
with an umloute [phonetic].

00:23:35.000 --> 00:23:38.430
And these peculiarities
suggested to Blor

00:23:38.430 --> 00:23:41.290
that Fiasta [phonetic] had
commissioned somebody quite well

00:23:41.290 --> 00:23:47.080 position:56%
informed about these remote northern
regions, in other words that the map

00:23:47.080 --> 00:23:49.500
and the text were the personal work

00:23:49.500 --> 00:23:52.920
of Claudius Clavus as
claimed on the map.

00:23:52.920 --> 00:23:55.400
And Blor was right.

00:23:55.400 --> 00:23:59.060
The O with slash implied
only in Norwegian

00:23:59.060 --> 00:24:03.230
and Danish is used correctly
throughout the map and text

00:24:03.230 --> 00:24:05.640
with a consistency that no French

00:24:05.640 --> 00:24:08.810
or Italian copies would
have been likely to manage,

00:24:08.810 --> 00:24:13.610
and by the way I am a
native Norwegian speaker.

00:24:13.610 --> 00:24:18.420
There are also numerous
other indications

00:24:18.420 --> 00:24:22.730
that Clavus had made the map
and the texts specifically

00:24:22.730 --> 00:24:25.230
for the cardinal's Geographia.

00:24:25.230 --> 00:24:33.060
Nonetheless, this agreement with
Blor arose in 1835, 45 rather,

00:24:33.060 --> 00:24:37.050
when the German scholar Gee Vites
[phonetic] blindly ignoring the O

00:24:37.050 --> 00:24:41.100
with a slash, doubted that the map

00:24:41.100 --> 00:24:47.130
and the text were personal
work of Claudius Clavus.

00:24:47.130 --> 00:24:51.430
[Inaudible] believed that both the
map and the text were anonymous

00:24:51.430 --> 00:24:56.180
and inferior copies of Clavus
originals was soon joined

00:24:56.180 --> 00:24:59.990
by an equally persistent
and wrong-headed conviction

00:24:59.990 --> 00:25:06.230
that post 1427 Clavus had made
an improved version of the map

00:25:06.230 --> 00:25:09.190
that had also followed
Ptolemaic precepts closely

00:25:09.190 --> 00:25:16.430 position:56%
but that later maps unfortunately
was lost and could not be consulted.

00:25:16.430 --> 00:25:19.730
Huh, where have we
heard that one before?

00:25:19.730 --> 00:25:25.680
Clavus had left Denmark for
the European mainland before,

00:25:25.680 --> 00:25:31.840
or around I should say, 1413
or 14, just when Ptolemy system

00:25:31.840 --> 00:25:36.540
of coordinates was
embraced farther south

00:25:36.540 --> 00:25:39.510
but had not yet reached Denmark.

00:25:39.510 --> 00:25:44.230
[ Background Noise ]

00:25:44.230 --> 00:25:47.490
Airplane throat.

00:25:47.490 --> 00:25:49.610
Had not yet reached Denmark,

00:25:49.610 --> 00:25:53.470
but the Danish cleric was
obviously a very quick learner

00:25:53.470 --> 00:25:57.650
because only a decade or so after
leaving home he based his map

00:25:57.650 --> 00:26:02.830
and text for Feastrus manuscript
on Ptolemy systems of coordinates

00:26:02.830 --> 00:26:09.630
as well as unfamiliarity with
the works of Adam O'Bramen

00:26:09.630 --> 00:26:13.400
and [inaudible] and on what he
knew personally about the geography

00:26:13.400 --> 00:26:15.510
of his northern home region.

00:26:15.510 --> 00:26:21.170
[ Background Noise ]

00:26:21.170 --> 00:26:25.240
While he knew from Adam O'Bramen's
history that Greenland lay west

00:26:25.240 --> 00:26:30.030
of Iceland, his grasp on Denmark's
Scandinavian neighbors failed him

00:26:30.030 --> 00:26:35.940
beyond the Dovre mountains in
Norway, and he had difficulties

00:26:35.940 --> 00:26:40.080
with Norwegian and
Swedish [inaudible].

00:26:40.080 --> 00:26:44.080
Only one such problem
concerns us here.

00:26:44.080 --> 00:26:52.160
On the Feaster [phonetic] map
but not on the accompanying text,

00:26:52.160 --> 00:26:57.670
Clavus wrote [foreign language]
where northern Sweden joins Norway.

00:26:57.670 --> 00:27:02.500 position:56%
And that became the second Greenland
on both the A and the B reductions

00:27:02.500 --> 00:27:08.530
in Nicholas Garmonis' manuscript
maps and their successors.

00:27:08.530 --> 00:27:14.950
The known whereabouts of
Feastrus' Geographia between 1427

00:27:14.950 --> 00:27:19.620
and 1835 show that the codex
could not have been seen

00:27:19.620 --> 00:27:23.780
by Nicholas Garmonis but by 1467,

00:27:23.780 --> 00:27:26.800
he had nevertheless
acquired information

00:27:26.800 --> 00:27:31.340
that inspired both his twin
Greenlands and his experiments

00:27:31.340 --> 00:27:37.520
with the country's shape, it's
nomenclature, and it's placement.

00:27:37.520 --> 00:27:41.530
We must look for an explanation in
the context that Clavus is known

00:27:41.530 --> 00:27:45.730
to have had with continental
scholars and in notes

00:27:45.730 --> 00:27:51.430
and sketches necessarily made in
preparation for Feastrus' codex.

00:27:51.430 --> 00:27:55.680
Alas, the whereabouts of any
such material is as unknown

00:27:55.680 --> 00:27:58.540
as the ultimate fate
of Clavus himself,

00:27:58.540 --> 00:28:02.710
but a trail suggesting
a Benedictine network

00:28:02.710 --> 00:28:06.830
and containing many later
interpolations has yielded nuggets

00:28:06.830 --> 00:28:10.920
of additional information that
could only have originated

00:28:10.920 --> 00:28:14.580
with Clavus although his own
affiliations were [inaudible].

00:28:14.580 --> 00:28:21.380
Next, a fantasy about an improved
companion text joined the notion

00:28:21.380 --> 00:28:27.240
that Clavus had laid a second
and improved map in 1904

00:28:27.240 --> 00:28:30.430
when the Danish scholar
Oxlong von Burenbul [phonetic]

00:28:30.430 --> 00:28:33.790
and Carles Pietrus [phonetic]
published the interpretations

00:28:33.790 --> 00:28:38.830 position:56%
of two 16th century manuscripts they
had discovered at the Royal Library

00:28:38.830 --> 00:28:42.160
of Vienna and called
the Vienna text.

00:28:42.160 --> 00:28:48.000 position:56%
They argued that travels in
Greenland and other Nordic countries

00:28:48.000 --> 00:28:54.420
after 1427 had enable Clavus
to produce both a second map

00:28:54.420 --> 00:28:59.270 position:56%
and an improved text that became the
prototype of the two Vienna texts

00:28:59.270 --> 00:29:03.200
and from which excerpts
had been published in 1515

00:29:03.200 --> 00:29:08.670
by Johannes Schoner and in 1518
by Francisco Zerenicus [phonetic].

00:29:08.670 --> 00:29:13.050
As soon as Burenbul and
Pietrus' book was out,

00:29:13.050 --> 00:29:16.410
Fischer began a correspondence
with Burenbul that lasted

00:29:16.410 --> 00:29:19.160
until the latter's death.

00:29:19.160 --> 00:29:23.790
He immediately assured his Danish
colleague of his own belief

00:29:23.790 --> 00:29:27.250
that Clavus had personal
knowledge of Greenland,

00:29:27.250 --> 00:29:31.470
a conviction he still held
when Burenbul died in 1911

00:29:31.470 --> 00:29:33.070
without revealing to Fischer

00:29:33.070 --> 00:29:37.760
that the Norwegian explorer Fetuv
Nonsen [phonetic] was certain

00:29:37.760 --> 00:29:40.200
that Clavus had never
been to Greenland.

00:29:40.200 --> 00:29:45.840
In a short monograph on Clavus that
Fischer published that same year

00:29:45.840 --> 00:29:52.040
in 1911, he insisted that Clavus
had explored up the Greenland coast

00:29:52.040 --> 00:29:58.940
as far as 70 degrees 2 second
northward, northern latitude.

00:29:58.940 --> 00:30:02.790
Because of his inability
to read either the primary

00:30:02.790 --> 00:30:08.880
or secondary material in Nordic
languages, plus his tendency

00:30:08.880 --> 00:30:13.050
to rather rigid thinking,
Fischer maintained his belief

00:30:13.050 --> 00:30:16.090
in the post 1427 information

00:30:16.090 --> 00:30:19.970
by Clavus had provided
Nicholas Garmonis

00:30:19.970 --> 00:30:22.430
with information about Greenland.

00:30:22.430 --> 00:30:27.040
When starting his thesis
research on the medieval Norse,

00:30:27.040 --> 00:30:32.910
Fischer had relied on help from the
Norwegian historian Gustuv Steim

00:30:32.910 --> 00:30:38.780
[phonetic], but Steim died in 1906,
and with Burenbul's death in 1911,

00:30:38.780 --> 00:30:43.960
Fischer lost his remaining
source of Nordic collegial help.

00:30:43.960 --> 00:30:51.800
He did nothing with his beloved
Norse from 1911 until 1932

00:30:51.800 --> 00:30:56.480
when he was 74 years old, and
the Swiss Austrian auction firm

00:30:56.480 --> 00:30:59.070
of Gilhof Antrantsburg
[phonetic] asked him

00:30:59.070 --> 00:31:05.120
to analyze a manuscript copied
from early Ptolemy Geographia.

00:31:05.120 --> 00:31:09.320
The volume's regional map of
Greenland, which reminded him

00:31:09.320 --> 00:31:14.530
of Ausmiller's [phonetic] Greenland
in the 1513 Strassberg Geographia,

00:31:14.530 --> 00:31:19.930
brought all his former
preoccupations back in full force.

00:31:19.930 --> 00:31:23.060
The Gilhof Antrantsburg
auction catalog

00:31:23.060 --> 00:31:27.760
for 1934 featured both
the Geographia codex

00:31:27.760 --> 00:31:32.850
with Fischer's analysis and
selected items from the library

00:31:32.850 --> 00:31:35.850
of Mikulov [phonetic]
castle in Moravia,

00:31:35.850 --> 00:31:38.790
a collection with which
Fischer was as familiar

00:31:38.790 --> 00:31:40.590
as with the auction house.

00:31:40.590 --> 00:31:45.190
[ Background Noise ]

00:31:45.190 --> 00:31:51.540
While the Library contained
damaged as well as undamaged items,

00:31:51.540 --> 00:31:55.750
the [inaudible] were excluded from
the auction catalog but a fragment

00:31:55.750 --> 00:31:58.100
of the Speculum Historiale

00:31:58.100 --> 00:32:01.140
by Vincent Aubove [phonetic]
was acceptable

00:32:01.140 --> 00:32:04.640
because Mikulov had provided
it with a new binding,

00:32:04.640 --> 00:32:08.820
and it was in generally good
condition except for leaves seven

00:32:08.820 --> 00:32:13.350
through 12, which had
been damaged by a nail.

00:32:13.350 --> 00:32:17.390
Interestingly, that fragment
represented the book following

00:32:17.390 --> 00:32:22.830 position:56%
immediately after the four
Speculum books that ended up at Yale

00:32:22.830 --> 00:32:24.630 position:56%
in association with the Vinland map.

00:32:24.630 --> 00:32:31.560
[ Background Noise ]

00:32:31.560 --> 00:32:36.440
On October 11, 1965, Yale
University Library announced

00:32:36.440 --> 00:32:41.280
that it possessed an unnamed
manuscript from about 1440

00:32:41.280 --> 00:32:45.290
that depicted the Norse
discovery of America.

00:32:45.290 --> 00:32:47.350
The item was dubbed the Vinland map

00:32:47.350 --> 00:32:51.480
because in the northwestern
Atlantic it showed a large island

00:32:51.480 --> 00:32:56.570
with two legends calling
the island Vinelanda insula.

00:32:56.570 --> 00:33:02.340
On that same day, Yale University
Press launched the Vinland map

00:33:02.340 --> 00:33:05.410
and the [inaudible] relation
by R.A. Skelton [phonetic],

00:33:05.410 --> 00:33:08.970
Thomas Marsten [phonetic], and
George Painter to authenticate

00:33:08.970 --> 00:33:12.570
and describe the map and
the formerly unknown version

00:33:12.570 --> 00:33:18.960
of Friar John de Plano Carpini's
[phonetic] account of his 1245

00:33:18.960 --> 00:33:22.100
to 47 embassy to the
great Kahn [phonetic],

00:33:22.100 --> 00:33:25.940
the so-called tarter [phonetic]
relation bound with the map

00:33:25.940 --> 00:33:29.100
at the time of purchase
in Switzerland.

00:33:29.100 --> 00:33:33.110
Four dilapidated books of
the Speculum Historiale

00:33:33.110 --> 00:33:37.720
in a comparatively modern binding
had turned up a little later

00:33:37.720 --> 00:33:41.550
as a sister manuscript to the map.

00:33:41.550 --> 00:33:47.550
No existing cartographic record of
Vinland was known not surprisingly,

00:33:47.550 --> 00:33:51.920
since the medieval Norse
neither used nor made maps.

00:33:51.920 --> 00:33:53.300
Therefore, it's appearance

00:33:53.300 --> 00:33:59.050
on otherwise conventional medieval
world map was remarkable indeed.

00:33:59.050 --> 00:34:02.590
However, the Vinland map
is a demonstrable fake,

00:34:02.590 --> 00:34:05.960
and like any other
artifact, fake or genuine,

00:34:05.960 --> 00:34:10.690
it reflects its maker's
preoccupations and environment.

00:34:10.690 --> 00:34:17.010
In 1974, the map's ink was found
to continue anatase crystals

00:34:17.010 --> 00:34:21.880
of a kind first available
commercially around 1920,

00:34:21.880 --> 00:34:27.290
and analysis was confirmed in 2002.

00:34:27.290 --> 00:34:32.830
Amazingly, this did not settle
the authenticity issue with those

00:34:32.830 --> 00:34:38.810 position:56%
of the map's defenders unable to
grasp that the additional historical

00:34:38.810 --> 00:34:42.560
and cartographic evidence
shows that this work

00:34:42.560 --> 00:34:47.970
in no way reflects Norse
geographical knowledge.

00:34:47.970 --> 00:34:53.090
Instead, it illustrates the 19th
century preoccupation with England,

00:34:53.090 --> 00:34:56.950
and that times mistaken belief
that the Norse experience

00:34:56.950 --> 00:35:01.790
with North American had
been a very short duration.

00:35:01.790 --> 00:35:07.630
Unfortunately, Skelton and
Marsten and Painter knew as little

00:35:07.630 --> 00:35:12.400
about the history and culture
of the medieval Norse as the man

00:35:12.400 --> 00:35:16.580
who had made the map and left
footprints so idiosyncratic

00:35:16.580 --> 00:35:21.030
that there is no mistaking
who's they are.

00:35:21.030 --> 00:35:25.360
The shorter of the two legends
near the island of Vinland says,

00:35:25.360 --> 00:35:30.690
island of Vinland discovered
by Bjarni and Leif and company.

00:35:30.690 --> 00:35:34.200
Well, the very first time that
Leif and Bjarni sailed off

00:35:34.200 --> 00:35:39.210
to America together and discovered
Vinland, that was Leif Eiriksson

00:35:39.210 --> 00:35:44.760
and Bjarni Hyalson [phonetic]
and that was in 1765.

00:35:44.760 --> 00:35:47.000
In the history of [inaudible]
Greenland

00:35:47.000 --> 00:35:48.940
by the German [inaudible]
David Grantz [phonetic]

00:35:48.940 --> 00:35:52.770
who had simply misread
Paul Ava Malay's [phonetic]

00:35:52.770 --> 00:35:54.070
[foreign language].

00:35:54.070 --> 00:35:59.610
Grantz' book appears
in the bibliography

00:35:59.610 --> 00:36:05.260
of the 1903 English translation of
Fischer's book on the Norse voyages

00:36:05.260 --> 00:36:10.340
to America, which had
a contorted explanation

00:36:10.340 --> 00:36:12.800
for the Icelandic [inaudible]
agreement

00:36:12.800 --> 00:36:16.240 position:56%
on who had first discovered America.

00:36:16.240 --> 00:36:19.910
In addition, sharing
his Ausmiller triumph

00:36:19.910 --> 00:36:25.480
with von Wieser had made Fischer
receptive to a broader definition

00:36:25.480 --> 00:36:31.500
of joint discovery, and his hero,
Adam O'Bramen, to whom both Vinland

00:36:31.500 --> 00:36:34.190
and Greenland were
islands had written

00:36:34.190 --> 00:36:40.110
that Vinland was an island
"discovered by many."

00:36:42.630 --> 00:36:47.280
The longer legend's description
of the land which byarnus

00:36:47.280 --> 00:36:50.340
and leiphus erissonius
discovered together,

00:36:50.340 --> 00:36:53.130
"a new land extremely fertile

00:36:53.130 --> 00:36:58.560
and even having vines" echos
Adam O'Bramen's statement

00:36:58.560 --> 00:37:01.390
that Vinland got its name because

00:37:01.390 --> 00:37:08.570 position:56%
"vines producing excellent wine grow
wild there" along the unsewn crops.

00:37:08.570 --> 00:37:13.320
The same legend also reveals
Fischer's tin ear for German names,

00:37:13.320 --> 00:37:19.370
non-German names, and his
unease with the suffix -son.

00:37:19.370 --> 00:37:23.830
He invariably referred to Leif
Eiriksson as the son of Eirik

00:37:23.830 --> 00:37:29.870
in his publications, and on the
Vinland map the name is Latinized

00:37:29.870 --> 00:37:33.210
to leiphus erissonius
as you can see.

00:37:33.210 --> 00:37:34.710
Understandably, he gave

00:37:34.710 --> 00:37:38.600
up on a Latin patrolimic
[phonetic] for Bjarni Hyalson.

00:37:38.600 --> 00:37:41.320
Henricus [inaudible]
bishop [inaudible]

00:37:41.320 --> 00:37:46.140
of Greenland is straightforward
but dating his arrival in Vinland

00:37:46.140 --> 00:37:51.630
to "the last year of our
most blessed Father Pascal,"

00:37:51.630 --> 00:37:58.820
whose papal reign was from 1099
to 1118 is not straightforward.

00:37:58.820 --> 00:38:04.930
In fact, this entire legend is part
of a complex riddle and reveals

00:38:04.930 --> 00:38:08.540
that the map's purpose is to
demonstrate that emissaries

00:38:08.540 --> 00:38:11.130
of the Roman church had succeeded

00:38:11.130 --> 00:38:17.230
in circumnavigating the
inhabited world at an early age.

00:38:17.230 --> 00:38:22.100
When Bishop Eric proceeded
to "wintery east" it was

00:38:22.100 --> 00:38:27.240
in the Columbian sense of to the
east, that is even so far west

00:38:27.240 --> 00:38:30.760
from proto [phonetic] America
that he gained the farthest east

00:38:30.760 --> 00:38:32.560
and thus completed the circle.

00:38:32.560 --> 00:38:37.040
[ Background Noise ]

00:38:37.040 --> 00:38:40.400
Father Fischer, a man of
immense rectitude and devotion

00:38:40.400 --> 00:38:44.860
to his church would have been
appalled by the later use made

00:38:44.860 --> 00:38:47.740
of the map he drew in the 1930's

00:38:47.740 --> 00:38:52.170
as a private catharsis
during a difficult time.

00:38:52.170 --> 00:38:55.190
