00:51:06.140 --> 00:51:10.040
with this text, with
these depictions.

00:51:10.040 --> 00:51:12.670
And what struck me in particular

00:51:12.670 --> 00:51:15.810
about this collection is
that it's a collection.

00:51:15.810 --> 00:51:18.220
There's more than one piece,
and they sort of relate

00:51:18.220 --> 00:51:19.520
to each other but they don't.

00:51:19.520 --> 00:51:22.390
As I'll point out at the end
of the talk, the Vinland map

00:51:22.390 --> 00:51:25.560
to me is fascinating
because it's a one-of.

00:51:25.560 --> 00:51:26.860
It's a single creation.

00:51:26.860 --> 00:51:29.460
These are multiple creations.

00:51:29.460 --> 00:51:32.490
This one's called the Sirdomap
Chart because it refers

00:51:32.490 --> 00:51:36.690
to what's terms a Syrian
navigator, so an Arab

00:51:36.690 --> 00:51:40.690
or Islamic navigator named
Sirdomab or Sirdomap.

00:51:40.690 --> 00:51:43.200
It's spelled differently
in two ways.

00:51:43.200 --> 00:51:46.800
And again already you see
very strange setup here

00:51:46.800 --> 00:51:50.480
where there is a map or chart.

00:51:50.480 --> 00:51:51.780
There's Arabic.

00:51:51.780 --> 00:51:56.100
There are Roman numerals, and
then there's a text below.

00:51:56.100 --> 00:52:00.690
And again it's all
about northeastern Asia,

00:52:00.690 --> 00:52:04.000
the furthest reaches of
Asia, and here we see

00:52:04.000 --> 00:52:07.860
that the text below
is written apparently

00:52:07.860 --> 00:52:10.530
by another daughter, Bellela Polo.

00:52:10.530 --> 00:52:13.860
Again, Marco Polo did have
three daughters, we know that.

00:52:13.860 --> 00:52:16.840
And this map has a set of toponyms

00:52:16.840 --> 00:52:20.990
and then a brief text
excerpt here says, my father,

00:52:20.990 --> 00:52:25.500
Marco Polo wishes me, Bellela,
to show this world map,

00:52:25.500 --> 00:52:29.210
it's not a world map, which
he obtained from the pilot,

00:52:29.210 --> 00:52:32.110 position:56%
the navigator, Biaxio Sirdomap, who,

00:52:32.110 --> 00:52:36.280
for at least thirty years sailed
the coast of Asia from Syria

00:52:36.280 --> 00:52:40.230
to the Far East, trading
in seal skins.

00:52:40.230 --> 00:52:43.930
And again, from a historical
perspective, this is very odd.

00:52:43.930 --> 00:52:49.790 position:56%
It's a combination of story of Marco
Polo with an account supposedly

00:52:49.790 --> 00:52:53.760
by his daughter talking
about an Arab navigator,

00:52:53.760 --> 00:52:57.510
talking about the extreme
northeast reaches of Asia,

00:52:57.510 --> 00:53:00.900
about which there's no
documentation in this period.

00:53:00.900 --> 00:53:05.520
So as a historian, I looked at
this without bias, and I was very,

00:53:05.520 --> 00:53:08.510
very puzzled, and I
want to highlight here

00:53:08.510 --> 00:53:13.760
in case I forget later, I had not
particular take on this in terms

00:53:13.760 --> 00:53:17.430
of is it a forgery, what's
the voracity of this account,

00:53:17.430 --> 00:53:20.260
but later when the book was
published, I got interviewed

00:53:20.260 --> 00:53:22.830
by the media a great
deal, newspapers,

00:53:22.830 --> 00:53:25.920 position:56%
the Smithsonian Magazine here in DC,

00:53:25.920 --> 00:53:28.120
and a report from the
Daily Telegraph said,

00:53:28.120 --> 00:53:29.640
well are they real or not.

00:53:29.640 --> 00:53:31.570
You know, that's all they want.

00:53:31.570 --> 00:53:35.390 position:56%
They just want that statement and I
said, you know, it's not about that.

00:53:35.390 --> 00:53:38.290
For me the book is
really about the content.

00:53:38.290 --> 00:53:40.020
I translated these.

00:53:40.020 --> 00:53:41.980
I deciphered some of the names.

00:53:41.980 --> 00:53:43.570
He says well what can
I quote you on?

00:53:43.570 --> 00:53:47.210
I said, quote me that I'm the
person who looked at the content.

00:53:47.210 --> 00:53:52.590
And he said that's very
boring, and I said, I know.

00:53:52.590 --> 00:53:53.890
[laughter] But that's
really the purpose.

00:53:53.890 --> 00:53:56.780
I wanted this as a
foundation for people to look

00:53:56.780 --> 00:53:59.610
and discuss this further.

00:53:59.610 --> 00:54:04.290 position:56%
If we then analyze the content a bit
further of this chart for example,

00:54:04.290 --> 00:54:09.770
we see again very peculiar
toponyms that again kind

00:54:09.770 --> 00:54:15.520
of imply a certain bias within the
material itself, because if we move

00:54:15.520 --> 00:54:21.160 position:56%
across the map, we see the different
toponyms have very specific names.

00:54:21.160 --> 00:54:26.510
The first says, peninsula de li
servi, peninsula of the Stags.

00:54:26.510 --> 00:54:31.110
Then peninsula of the phoca
marina, which are marine seals,

00:54:31.110 --> 00:54:36.590
and then valle conzonta e giazata,
so a connected frozen valley.

00:54:36.590 --> 00:54:40.560
So you really get this feeling
of remote northeast Asia.

00:54:40.560 --> 00:54:44.390
Island of women, anything Italian
has to have an island of women

00:54:44.390 --> 00:54:46.990
of course, Isola delle Femmine.

00:54:46.990 --> 00:54:50.130
There's a long tradition of
this mythical island of women

00:54:50.130 --> 00:54:54.380
on cartography, and then
the gulf of the mangi,

00:54:54.380 --> 00:54:56.350
or the manchuse [phonetic].

00:54:56.350 --> 00:55:02.330
So what's strange again is
you have an Italian and Arabic

00:55:02.330 --> 00:55:05.000
and it implies again a
knowledge of a region

00:55:05.000 --> 00:55:09.230
about which we have no
documentation in this period.

00:55:09.230 --> 00:55:12.860
This is the famous Map with
Ship, which you will get to see

00:55:12.860 --> 00:55:15.150
if you come to the
Library of Congress.

00:55:15.150 --> 00:55:19.870
Hessler himself has done some
work looking at writing on this

00:55:19.870 --> 00:55:24.570
and some scratches in the
velum that also reveal writing.

00:55:24.570 --> 00:55:26.760 position:56%
This is the most famous of the maps.

00:55:26.760 --> 00:55:31.060
If you google Rossi maps, you'll
see this because the Library

00:55:31.060 --> 00:55:36.150 position:56%
of Congress put up a very nice
high-res image, and it's also famous

00:55:36.150 --> 00:55:38.610
because it seems to
suggest something,

00:55:38.610 --> 00:55:40.800
which I'll highlight later.

00:55:40.800 --> 00:55:42.240
Again, very strange.

00:55:42.240 --> 00:55:46.870
It has a faint drawing of a ship
to the left, and apparent seal

00:55:46.870 --> 00:55:50.290
of the Polo family, and
then the map on the right.

00:55:50.290 --> 00:55:55.270
And I was most interested in
the map because it's an odd map,

00:55:55.270 --> 00:55:59.620
and it has a "Chinese inscription."

00:55:59.620 --> 00:56:03.970
It was kind of odd that I came
to this map speaking Chinese,

00:56:03.970 --> 00:56:05.460
which was pure coincidence.

00:56:05.460 --> 00:56:07.170
I did not write this.

00:56:07.170 --> 00:56:11.640
One of the reasons I can tell you I
didn't write this is the characters

00:56:11.640 --> 00:56:15.660
are not written by a
person who knows Chinese.

00:56:15.660 --> 00:56:19.950
And this was something that had
not been pointed out before.

00:56:19.950 --> 00:56:22.120
Chinse has what's called
a stroke order.

00:56:22.120 --> 00:56:24.370
If you write any character,
there's a stroke order

00:56:24.370 --> 00:56:26.780
which basically moves top
to bottom, left to right.

00:56:26.780 --> 00:56:29.100
There's a way of writing Chinese.

00:56:29.100 --> 00:56:34.260 position:56%
If I were to hand you a Chinese menu
and say copy General Tsao's chicken

00:56:34.260 --> 00:56:39.190
in Chinese, what it says, you
would draw the character sort

00:56:39.190 --> 00:56:42.730
of copying the lines, and
it would look very awkward.

00:56:42.730 --> 00:56:45.060
The proportions would be wrong.

00:56:45.060 --> 00:56:46.960
And in fact that's
what you see here.

00:56:46.960 --> 00:56:50.540
So whoever did this, you can
recognize the characters,

00:56:50.540 --> 00:56:52.850
but whoever wrote this was copying

00:56:52.850 --> 00:56:58.170
from some Chinese thing
sitting next to him or her.

00:56:58.170 --> 00:57:01.030
So when you look at the characters
then, some of them you can make

00:57:01.030 --> 00:57:03.120
out fairly well, and I did.

00:57:03.120 --> 00:57:05.030
I transcribed them.

00:57:05.030 --> 00:57:07.000
But they don't really say anything.

00:57:07.000 --> 00:57:09.380
There's not a sentence here.

00:57:09.380 --> 00:57:12.300
You see a variety of
characters, the character bai,

00:57:12.300 --> 00:57:15.740
which means one hundred;
chu, which means to go out;

00:57:15.740 --> 00:57:19.450
qi, seven; si, meaning four.

00:57:19.450 --> 00:57:23.200
So there are characters here,
but there's no sentence here,

00:57:23.200 --> 00:57:26.170
which is very frustrating
for a researcher.

00:57:26.170 --> 00:57:29.810
However, it's interesting because
whoever put these together,

00:57:29.810 --> 00:57:35.340 position:56%
whether it was a forger, whether it
was someone who genuinely was trying

00:57:35.340 --> 00:57:38.740
to collate some kind
of cartographic data.

00:57:38.740 --> 00:57:41.190
They were looking at
something Chinese.

00:57:41.190 --> 00:57:44.000
They were looking at
something that had Arabic text.

00:57:44.000 --> 00:57:48.580
And you get this very
odd amalgam here.

00:57:48.580 --> 00:57:53.660
The Map with Ship, again, also has
these kind of numbered toponyms

00:57:53.660 --> 00:58:01.260 position:56%
that again refer to very similar set
of places moving towards the east,

00:58:01.260 --> 00:58:04.560
and if you look at them again,
there's this attribution

00:58:04.560 --> 00:58:09.320
to the Saracens, to Arab
navigators, these remote islands,

00:58:09.320 --> 00:58:12.240
cattigara [phonetic],
which you find in Ptolemy.

00:58:12.240 --> 00:58:16.980
Again, a reference to animals
that would live in these regions.

00:58:16.980 --> 00:58:19.750
Lioni marini, sea lions.

00:58:19.750 --> 00:58:22.980
And then these islands connected
to the peninsula of the stags.

00:58:22.980 --> 00:58:27.040
You can imagine these reindeer
running across remote corner

00:58:27.040 --> 00:58:30.120
of Siberia and northeastern Asia.

00:58:30.120 --> 00:58:37.320
Of course, what the media globbed
onto was the fact that this section

00:58:37.320 --> 00:58:40.410
of the map looks just like the
Bering Strait, and if it looks

00:58:40.410 --> 00:58:43.690
like the Bering Strait, it
must be the Bering Strait,

00:58:43.690 --> 00:58:46.840
and I argued strenuously
against this,

00:58:46.840 --> 00:58:51.230
and in fact going all the
way back to my PhD thesis,

00:58:51.230 --> 00:58:52.750
I have a long history of arguing

00:58:52.750 --> 00:58:55.480
that with cartography
things may look alike.

00:58:55.480 --> 00:58:57.920
It doesn't mean they're
the same thing.

00:58:57.920 --> 00:59:01.220
But if you go online, you'll see
this in a whole bunch of magazines

00:59:01.220 --> 00:59:03.680
and newspapers, and I like
to show audiences this

00:59:03.680 --> 00:59:05.450
because it's interesting.

00:59:05.450 --> 00:59:08.770
You do see this ring of
islands, which look sort

00:59:08.770 --> 00:59:13.090
of like the Aleutian Islands, but
we cannot make any firm statement

00:59:13.090 --> 00:59:18.020
as to the identity of what this
map is referring to in terms

00:59:18.020 --> 00:59:21.310
of present day cartography.

00:59:21.310 --> 00:59:27.470 position:56%
Another daughter, Fantina Polo, also
has her name on one of these maps.

00:59:27.470 --> 00:59:34.330
This is a very odd map in terms
of its frame, the strange ellipse,

00:59:34.330 --> 00:59:39.900
and again it has inscriptions, and
again it has a series of toponyms.

00:59:39.900 --> 00:59:43.620
And it was this map that
struck me in a way as one

00:59:43.620 --> 00:59:47.390
of the most interesting because
the toponyms when I looked

00:59:47.390 --> 00:59:51.170
at them puzzled me
literally for several years.

00:59:51.170 --> 00:59:55.300
I was like what is this because
it's Italian, Latinated Italian,

00:59:55.300 --> 01:00:00.380
but some of the words were not
even remotely Latin or Italian,

01:00:00.380 --> 01:00:04.570
and when I looked at them, well the
first was Zipangu, which is Japan.

01:00:04.570 --> 01:00:08.700
That's how Marco Polo period
text referred to Japan.

01:00:08.700 --> 01:00:10.160
That's not strange.

01:00:10.160 --> 01:00:12.740
The first one, Serica,
that's just the word

01:00:12.740 --> 01:00:16.600
for China, and Tartary, Tartaria.

01:00:16.600 --> 01:00:21.670
But then toponym number three Uan
Scian, you'd say it in Italian,

01:00:21.670 --> 01:00:24.060
and then the next one, To Qiu.

01:00:24.060 --> 01:00:25.850
And then the next one, Da Han,

01:00:25.850 --> 01:00:30.040
or in Venetian the C would
be pronounced H, Ta Can.

01:00:30.040 --> 01:00:31.870
And then Focan.

01:00:31.870 --> 01:00:33.800
And the final one, the eastern sea.

01:00:33.800 --> 01:00:37.650
But I looked at those middle ones,
and I said those just sound very,

01:00:37.650 --> 01:00:41.310
very strange to me, and
again I already had this idea

01:00:41.310 --> 01:00:46.420
that the renderer of these maps was
trying to take something foreign

01:00:46.420 --> 01:00:52.500
to him or her and put it
into some kind of Italian,

01:00:52.500 --> 01:00:55.290
something that would be
understandable to them.

01:00:55.290 --> 01:00:59.360
And it finally struck me that
the third one, the fifth one,

01:00:59.360 --> 01:01:04.600
and the sixth one were Chinese,
and I only knew that by pure chance

01:01:04.600 --> 01:01:06.760
because there's a famous
story of Fu Sang,

01:01:06.760 --> 01:01:09.860
which some of you may know
about, it's this Chinese tale

01:01:09.860 --> 01:01:12.800
of a Buddhist monk
that supposedly travels

01:01:12.800 --> 01:01:15.700
to the distant reaches
beyond the ocean,

01:01:15.700 --> 01:01:19.320
but the place names actually
are referred to sequentially

01:01:19.320 --> 01:01:23.160
in the myth, so you have Uan Scian
[phonetic], which is Wen Shen

01:01:23.160 --> 01:01:29.160 position:56%
in Chinese, and that literally means
a tattooed body, like the Ainu,

01:01:29.160 --> 01:01:32.260
a marked body, Chen means a body.

01:01:32.260 --> 01:01:36.720
And then Da Han would be,
actually I explained it here.

01:01:36.720 --> 01:01:41.530
Da Han would be the great country
of the Han, of the Chinese.

01:01:41.530 --> 01:01:44.650
So again you're going in
order because according

01:01:44.650 --> 01:01:48.410
to the original story
in the Liang Shu,

01:01:48.410 --> 01:01:51.280
in fact there's this
progression of places going

01:01:51.280 --> 01:01:52.670
to the distant northeast.

01:01:52.670 --> 01:01:57.410
Wen Shen, the tattooed or marked
bodies that may refer to the Ainu.

01:01:57.410 --> 01:02:01.740
Da Han wall [phonetic], the great
Han country, said to be east.

01:02:01.740 --> 01:02:05.680
And then finally to the
distant east, you have Fu Sang,

01:02:05.680 --> 01:02:09.880
and that Sang refers
to the mulberry tree.

01:02:09.880 --> 01:02:12.740
So it's interesting that you
have this map that's attributed

01:02:12.740 --> 01:02:18.000
to Marco Polo's daughter that has
these toponyms written in Italian,

01:02:18.000 --> 01:02:21.310
written in Venetian dialect,
and yet they're referring

01:02:21.310 --> 01:02:24.310
to a Chinese story,
a mythical story,

01:02:24.310 --> 01:02:26.510
and that to me was
the most interesting.

01:02:26.510 --> 01:02:30.490
Not in terms of proving a
voyage beyond the Pacific,

01:02:30.490 --> 01:02:33.240
but just looking at sources.

01:02:33.240 --> 01:02:36.750
And what's fascinating
is that this story

01:02:36.750 --> 01:02:41.470
of Fu Sang was actually only
known in Europe in the 1700's.

01:02:41.470 --> 01:02:46.320
A sinologist, a kind of strange
sinologist named Joseph de Guignes,

01:02:46.320 --> 01:02:48.870
who some of you may know,

01:02:48.870 --> 01:02:53.630
he believed that Chinese characters
were based on Egyptian hieroglyphs,

01:02:53.630 --> 01:02:58.700
but he was a sinologist, and
he did understand Chinese.

01:02:58.700 --> 01:03:04.460
He only found that text, the Fu
Sang text, the Liang Shu text,

01:03:04.460 --> 01:03:11.100
he only found that in the 1700's,
and he presented it about 1761

01:03:11.100 --> 01:03:17.390
in France, and he took the Chinese
names and Romanized them via French

01:03:17.390 --> 01:03:18.870
through the French language.

01:03:18.870 --> 01:03:23.570
So what's very strange is that
we see here it done in Italian.

01:03:23.570 --> 01:03:32.350
And in fact these place names
became put onto maps in the 1700's.

01:03:32.350 --> 01:03:36.900
This is a map, I forget the map
maker here, but he's actually drawn

01:03:36.900 --> 01:03:41.840
across the bottom, let me see
here, he says [foreign language].

01:03:41.840 --> 01:03:53.840
So it's like the root of the
Chinese to America in 458.

01:03:53.840 --> 01:03:58.430
So obviously in the 1700's people
believed this tale as a true tale

01:03:58.430 --> 01:04:00.170
of journeys across the Pacific.

01:04:00.170 --> 01:04:04.520 position:56%
But what's interesting is that the
Polo map suggested somebody had this

01:04:04.520 --> 01:04:09.110
idea much earlier, had read
this Chinese story much earlier,

01:04:09.110 --> 01:04:12.090
and had essentially brought
it to Europe much earlier.

01:04:12.090 --> 01:04:15.960
So to me this was the most
interesting aspect of these maps,

01:04:15.960 --> 01:04:21.270
a very strange synthesis of
Chinese and European sources.

01:04:21.270 --> 01:04:26.200
The conclusions are
interesting since this first part

01:04:26.200 --> 01:04:30.770
of the conference really is
about fact or fiction, and again,

01:04:30.770 --> 01:04:35.340
when I wrote the book, and when
I was talking to the University

01:04:35.340 --> 01:04:38.770
of Chicago about the book,
I said I really just want

01:04:38.770 --> 01:04:41.070
to be the person examining
the contents.

01:04:41.070 --> 01:04:43.060
I want to translate everything.

01:04:43.060 --> 01:04:45.680
I want to draw some
analogies, like I just did.

01:04:45.680 --> 01:04:52.890 position:56%
I want to look at content, but it's
very hard to make fixed conclusions.

01:04:54.460 --> 01:04:57.330
You have here some
interesting possibilities

01:04:57.330 --> 01:04:58.930
that the content suggests.

01:04:58.930 --> 01:05:02.330
You know, the book, my book
really looks at analysis

01:05:02.330 --> 01:05:07.570
of the maps themselves, translation
of the text, again tries to put it

01:05:07.570 --> 01:05:10.860
in context of other
cartographic work,

01:05:10.860 --> 01:05:14.010
but it's not quite a
repeat of the Vinland map.

01:05:14.010 --> 01:05:18.420
First of all, there are more
documents, which is interesting.

01:05:18.420 --> 01:05:22.290
The other is that there's
connections between the two.

01:05:22.290 --> 01:05:25.340
They use this sort of
same toponymic system,

01:05:25.340 --> 01:05:27.660
sometimes the same
places are referred

01:05:27.660 --> 01:05:29.920
to in one map and another map.

01:05:29.920 --> 01:05:33.390
They're tied together by
supposedly all being penned

01:05:33.390 --> 01:05:36.140
by Marco Polo's daughters.

01:05:36.140 --> 01:05:38.510
They are also different
from the Vinland map

01:05:38.510 --> 01:05:40.470
in that there's no single suspect,

01:05:40.470 --> 01:05:43.570
at least that I was
able to identify.

01:05:43.570 --> 01:05:48.480
Even Rossi himself I don't think
quite had the chops let's say

01:05:48.480 --> 01:05:52.720
to crank all of these
out as a collection.

01:05:52.720 --> 01:05:55.170
Also, it's not clear
what the motive is.

01:05:55.170 --> 01:05:59.170
Usually when we look at forgeries
there may be a political motive,

01:05:59.170 --> 01:06:04.160
a socioeconomic motive, just
a straight monetary motive.

01:06:04.160 --> 01:06:06.700 position:56%
You know, I am making these to sell.

01:06:06.700 --> 01:06:09.690
And in fact it's interesting
in Rossi's history,

01:06:09.690 --> 01:06:12.860
we don't have any record of him
trying to sell them to the Library

01:06:12.860 --> 01:06:17.270
of Congress for example or sell
them to anyone else, so it's very,

01:06:17.270 --> 01:06:23.020 position:56%
very strange whoever created these
had some motive, but it's not really

01:06:23.020 --> 01:06:27.820
in line with what we might see in
the history of other forgeries.

