01:13:19.690 --> 01:13:22.780
We'll see a little bit more
about that in a minute.

01:13:22.780 --> 01:13:25.640
So what is the nature of the maps?

01:13:25.640 --> 01:13:29.620
There are a number of what I call
subsets, groups within the corpus

01:13:29.620 --> 01:13:34.340
that have shared characteristics,
so this is one subset

01:13:34.340 --> 01:13:38.050
where there are a lot of greens and
yellows, and across the landscapes

01:13:38.050 --> 01:13:41.540
of the towns represented,
we have birds

01:13:41.540 --> 01:13:44.630
and snakes and large human heads.

01:13:44.630 --> 01:13:49.280
This is another group that has
the palette of browns largely,

01:13:49.280 --> 01:13:54.160
buildings painted white, and so on.

01:13:54.160 --> 01:13:57.590
And here's another group that
the cartographer really liked

01:13:57.590 --> 01:14:00.040
to use sharp, notable angles.

01:14:00.040 --> 01:14:03.180
So I'm thinking there were
several people who made the maps.

01:14:03.180 --> 01:14:06.320
There was a fellow named
Manuel Tello who was pointed

01:14:06.320 --> 01:14:08.450
out in the course case
as being the map maker,

01:14:08.450 --> 01:14:12.660
but I think that among the 18 men
there must have been a few working

01:14:12.660 --> 01:14:13.960
on this.

01:14:13.960 --> 01:14:15.710
Maybe he taught some
others how to make maps,

01:14:15.710 --> 01:14:18.490
and so there are multiple styles.

01:14:18.490 --> 01:14:24.750
And so one of the things I work
with students is to identify

01:14:24.750 --> 01:14:28.090
when you see a map that might
be part of a larger corpus

01:14:28.090 --> 01:14:30.980
to see what is it about
that map that makes it seem

01:14:30.980 --> 01:14:32.280
to fit in with that group.

01:14:32.280 --> 01:14:39.570
So I put up here for you some
other maps of central Mexico,

01:14:39.570 --> 01:14:45.120
and there's one from this
Puebla-Tlaxcala group.

01:14:45.120 --> 01:14:47.320
By the way they were
made about 1870,

01:14:47.320 --> 01:14:50.870
purporting to be colonial
Mexican maps,

01:14:50.870 --> 01:14:54.340
and so I have some colonial maps
here, one from the 16th century

01:14:54.340 --> 01:14:58.770
and two from the 17th and
one of these 1870 maps.

01:14:58.770 --> 01:15:01.910
And I hope that you can
see which one it is.

01:15:01.910 --> 01:15:05.230 position:56%
Does anyone want to venture a guess?

01:15:05.230 --> 01:15:10.660 position:56%
It's the lower left here, so it has,
this is one of the green and yellow,

01:15:10.660 --> 01:15:16.460
but it also has those buildings
painted white, and it's, you know,

01:15:16.460 --> 01:15:20.650
it looks rather romantic, landscape
like compared to the others.

01:15:20.650 --> 01:15:22.820
The upper left is the 16th century,

01:15:22.820 --> 01:15:29.160
very much indigenous cartographic
example, and then the other two

01:15:29.160 --> 01:15:34.410
from the 17th century on
the right, top and bottom.

01:15:34.410 --> 01:15:38.600
So here's a closeup of the one
that was in the lower left.

01:15:38.600 --> 01:15:40.640
This is not here in the
Library of Congress.

01:15:40.640 --> 01:15:43.340
This one, a vendor of Rare
Books and Manuscripts,

01:15:43.340 --> 01:15:47.570
contacted me in 2012 saying,
you know, what can you tell me

01:15:47.570 --> 01:15:51.730
about this map, and right away I
said, oh, that looks like it fits

01:15:51.730 --> 01:15:58.230
with this corpus of the Yanez-Tello
Workshop that I'm calling it.

01:15:58.230 --> 01:16:01.230
Here's the document that's in the
court case here in the Library

01:16:01.230 --> 01:16:05.640
of Congress that shows the
arrest record of Melecio Yanez,

01:16:05.640 --> 01:16:10.550
who was sort of the ring leader and
Manuel Tello and some other men.

01:16:10.550 --> 01:16:14.510
Vicente Poblano, Antonio
Guerrero, these are typical names

01:16:14.510 --> 01:16:19.430
of urban dwelling, mixed heritage
men, probably came from Puebla.

01:16:19.430 --> 01:16:24.040
Francisco Coca, now that
last name is in line

01:16:24.040 --> 01:16:28.950
with an indigenous community elite
from one of the Townsend vaults,

01:16:28.950 --> 01:16:33.790 position:56%
so it's, so there's some involvement
of indigenous people in the making

01:16:33.790 --> 01:16:38.500
of these maps for indigenous towns,
but it's largely not their work.

01:16:38.500 --> 01:16:41.120
This is another document
in the court case,

01:16:41.120 --> 01:16:47.070
which shows the profit motive if
you will and making these maps.

01:16:47.070 --> 01:16:51.690
The man made maps and titles from
more than 20 communities as I said,

01:16:51.690 --> 01:16:54.440
and in this case, for
example, made 15 visits

01:16:54.440 --> 01:16:57.830
to one town to collect payments.

01:16:57.830 --> 01:17:03.070
And for me this is a risky
behavior because for one thing

01:17:03.070 --> 01:17:05.040
if you're doing something
surreptitious,

01:17:05.040 --> 01:17:07.590
the authorities are
likely to see you if you're

01:17:07.590 --> 01:17:10.120
around to different
towns collecting money.

01:17:10.120 --> 01:17:15.390
Also I work on another workshop
from the valley of Toluca, Mexico,

01:17:15.390 --> 01:17:20.060 position:56%
where the collector was in fact
murdered by a town that was very fed

01:17:20.060 --> 01:17:23.250
up with making these payments,
and the money was rather,

01:17:23.250 --> 01:17:25.640
it was expensive, and it was
hard to get the money together.

01:17:25.640 --> 01:17:30.970
And this document, another one,
they kept very meticulous records

01:17:30.970 --> 01:17:33.990
of all the monies they collected
from the different towns

01:17:33.990 --> 01:17:36.340
and who went and did
what, so it was very easy

01:17:36.340 --> 01:17:39.770
for the criminal case
layer to figure this out.

01:17:39.770 --> 01:17:43.500
I just show this one because it
mentions don Francisco Cahuantzi,

01:17:43.500 --> 01:17:49.500
who was again an indigenous
person, an elite, and some relative

01:17:49.500 --> 01:17:52.820
of his became governor of the stat
of Glasgow in the 19th century,

01:17:52.820 --> 01:17:56.010
so it's really intriguing
to me who this man was,

01:17:56.010 --> 01:17:58.070
but he was lesser known

01:17:58.070 --> 01:18:01.120
than Prospero Cahuantzi,
who was the governor.

01:18:01.120 --> 01:18:04.560
So I don't know a lot about
that particular fellow.

01:18:04.560 --> 01:18:09.050
Here's an example of a map
and the accompanying titles.

01:18:09.050 --> 01:18:14.500
For one particular town,
they had to pay 299 pesos,

01:18:14.500 --> 01:18:19.090 position:56%
a daily wage was a third of a peso,
so this is a lot of money for humble

01:18:19.090 --> 01:18:21.850
and small indigenous
communities to come up with.

01:18:21.850 --> 01:18:28.330
So they were, there was a monetary
motive to a large extent here.

01:18:28.330 --> 01:18:31.400 position:56%
The documents that go with the maps,

01:18:31.400 --> 01:18:35.030
very fitting elements
are say a royal provision

01:18:35.030 --> 01:18:38.660
that says this town has this
territory and we recognize it,

01:18:38.660 --> 01:18:43.520 position:56%
and then there is a process that
provides a protection of possession,

01:18:43.520 --> 01:18:47.500
boundary survey, measurements,
and then result is a map.

01:18:47.500 --> 01:18:51.640
Now that's the official colonial
administrative kind of record.

01:18:51.640 --> 01:18:57.340 position:56%
Now these have, in addition to those
faked elements of the town title,

01:18:57.340 --> 01:18:59.570
they have some more things
that they have pulled

01:18:59.570 --> 01:19:03.950
from the more indigenous
historical record tradition.

01:19:03.950 --> 01:19:06.480
So portraits of town founders.

01:19:06.480 --> 01:19:08.530
A code of arms.

01:19:08.530 --> 01:19:10.400
A narrative of the town founding.

01:19:10.400 --> 01:19:14.970
A narrative of the first
church and the use of Nahuati.

01:19:14.970 --> 01:19:18.060
I'm not saying that, you
know, using Nahuati was fake.

01:19:18.060 --> 01:19:21.820
It was an internal thing that
many towns had records in Nahuati,

01:19:21.820 --> 01:19:24.740
the indigenous language
of the central Mexicans,

01:19:24.740 --> 01:19:29.560
but for a colonial official
record to have that was unusual.

01:19:29.560 --> 01:19:33.270
So here's an example
of one of these titles.

01:19:33.270 --> 01:19:39.580
A town founder, supposedly the
portrait from the year 1623,

01:19:39.580 --> 01:19:43.480
but his clothes immediately
convey that's not the case.

01:19:43.480 --> 01:19:46.900
You know, if this is a copy
of something earlier, okay,

01:19:46.900 --> 01:19:51.860
made in the 19th century perhaps,

01:19:51.860 --> 01:19:55.140
but it claims to be
a [foreign language].

01:19:55.140 --> 01:19:58.710
They use these true, you
know, original and so

01:19:58.710 --> 01:20:01.730
on words all the time, which
when there is copy made,

01:20:01.730 --> 01:20:06.800
it was always a true and loyal copy
would be stated, so they're bending

01:20:06.800 --> 01:20:11.090
over backwards to say this is not
a copy, but it's not original.

01:20:11.090 --> 01:20:14.720
And here's an example
of a coat of arms in one

01:20:14.720 --> 01:20:17.190
of these bundles of town titles.

01:20:17.190 --> 01:20:20.630
And they say specifically that
the town gave this coat of arms

01:20:20.630 --> 01:20:24.300
to the viceroy, which is backwards
because in most communities

01:20:24.300 --> 01:20:27.200
where they had a coat of arms
that was given to them by the kind

01:20:27.200 --> 01:20:30.330
or the viceroy, you know,
that's the direction it went.

01:20:30.330 --> 01:20:32.400
It went, you know,
authorities to the town

01:20:32.400 --> 01:20:34.410
and then they proudly
would, you know,

01:20:34.410 --> 01:20:37.560
show it in their community center.

01:20:37.560 --> 01:20:40.750
But this one they said the
town gave this to the viceroy.

01:20:40.750 --> 01:20:44.730
Well it's crazy, but
anyway, it's interesting.

01:20:44.730 --> 01:20:47.930
So here we have the boundary
measurements, the standard kind

01:20:47.930 --> 01:20:52.260
of thing, but the page
itself is very odd.

01:20:52.260 --> 01:20:54.370
It says it's from 1758.

01:20:54.370 --> 01:20:56.340
The handwriting says no it isn't.

01:20:56.340 --> 01:20:59.160
There's a big stamp right
on top of the writing.

01:20:59.160 --> 01:21:03.310
That's not a sealed paper, official
colonial sealed paper had the stamp

01:21:03.310 --> 01:21:06.560
in the upper left corner, and
then you wrote next to it.

01:21:06.560 --> 01:21:07.860
You didn't write over it.

01:21:07.860 --> 01:21:10.600
And so this is, the
stamp has come later

01:21:10.600 --> 01:21:12.570
and been put on top of the writing.

01:21:12.570 --> 01:21:14.700
The orthography full of K's.

01:21:14.700 --> 01:21:18.520
The letter K came into
Mexico in the 19th century.

01:21:18.520 --> 01:21:20.520
It was definitely not there
in the colonial period

01:21:20.520 --> 01:21:22.530
from many records I know of.

01:21:22.530 --> 01:21:25.650
So, you know, it's
just very strange.

01:21:25.650 --> 01:21:30.690
So another example of the boundary
survey, the royal provision,

01:21:30.690 --> 01:21:34.050
supposedly from these
years, has three stamps.

01:21:34.050 --> 01:21:36.090
You wouldn't have a
page with three stamps.

01:21:36.090 --> 01:21:38.730
Usually just one in the
upper left-hand corner.

01:21:38.730 --> 01:21:42.780
Typically too it would have then
some text that gave, with the stamp

01:21:42.780 --> 01:21:48.420
that gave the years that
the paper was made and sold.

01:21:48.420 --> 01:21:53.020 position:56%
This is protection of possession
for one community, again full of K's

01:21:53.020 --> 01:21:56.780
and so on, and misspellings
and other things.

01:21:56.780 --> 01:22:01.630
This is a peculiar signature,
a hand print and a cross.

01:22:01.630 --> 01:22:04.960
Sometimes, you know, we do see
crosses in colonial manuscripts,

01:22:04.960 --> 01:22:09.200
not so many hand prints, and I
would just think that's very fun

01:22:09.200 --> 01:22:12.520 position:56%
if you're a, you know, a fingerprint
analyst, you could figure

01:22:12.520 --> 01:22:15.170
out who this was, but of course
the person is now long dead,

01:22:15.170 --> 01:22:16.800
but enjoyable.

01:22:16.800 --> 01:22:19.150
Problematic dates.

01:22:19.150 --> 01:22:23.120
This is one document that
says onyo day [phonetic] 1546,

01:22:23.120 --> 01:22:27.270
the year of 1546 when it's not
at all the right handwriting

01:22:27.270 --> 01:22:34.610
for that period or this statement
on a map that says, you know, 1760,

01:22:34.610 --> 01:22:38.870
and again full of K's and so on.

01:22:38.870 --> 01:22:43.490
And here a map, totally
original, from the town.

01:22:43.490 --> 01:22:45.640
Maps didn't say totally original.

01:22:45.640 --> 01:22:49.170
They only said, you know,
totally faithful to the original

01:22:49.170 --> 01:22:53.150
when it was a copy, as we see
in the bottom example here.

01:22:53.150 --> 01:22:59.700 position:56%
Peculiar orthography, so again just
kind of sharing with you the methods

01:22:59.700 --> 01:23:05.600
of deconstructing this syelo,
the word for sky, S, Y, E, L, O,

01:23:05.600 --> 01:23:07.790
just unheard of spelling.

01:23:07.790 --> 01:23:10.880
You know, maybe C and
S's were substituted,

01:23:10.880 --> 01:23:14.760
but the I for Y with
the S just strange.

01:23:14.760 --> 01:23:19.650
Eskritura with a K, no, no, never.

01:23:19.650 --> 01:23:20.950
And so on.

01:23:20.950 --> 01:23:25.150
So Eskribano Real y
publiko, this notary.

01:23:25.150 --> 01:23:27.760
Notaries typically
abbreviated real y publiko,

01:23:27.760 --> 01:23:29.060
they got so sick of writing.

01:23:29.060 --> 01:23:31.350
Even the work escribano
was abbreviated,

01:23:31.350 --> 01:23:33.520
so the whole thing would
be abbreviated here.

01:23:33.520 --> 01:23:37.130
It's all spelled out like a
very big amateur might do,

01:23:37.130 --> 01:23:39.520
but even that, it's just very rare.

01:23:39.520 --> 01:23:45.570 position:56%
A lot of these titles were tied with
ropes in legahos [phonetic] bundles,

01:23:45.570 --> 01:23:47.610
and those ropes over
the years of being tied

01:23:47.610 --> 01:23:52.700 position:56%
and untied would create a lot of
wear, which this one page, you know,

01:23:52.700 --> 01:23:55.870
looks, it looks something
like the wear that you see,

01:23:55.870 --> 01:24:00.330
but this was burned in to make it
look like it was worn by robes,

01:24:00.330 --> 01:24:04.890
and yet the page underneath is not
worn, and that would be strange.

01:24:04.890 --> 01:24:07.970
So very curious, peculiar.

01:24:07.970 --> 01:24:12.730
Here's another example of
an oddity, lined paper.

01:24:12.730 --> 01:24:15.890
We didn't have lined paper
in the colonial period.

01:24:15.890 --> 01:24:18.310
You go in the archives,
you won't find it.

01:24:18.310 --> 01:24:22.590
So very 19th century
flavor right here.

01:24:22.590 --> 01:24:26.380
And going back to those seals
that I already pointed out.

01:24:26.380 --> 01:24:29.340
These are fabricated.

01:24:29.340 --> 01:24:34.410
They misspell the word seal
itself, so, you know, duh,

01:24:34.410 --> 01:24:37.340
but they also made two
or three different kinds,

01:24:37.340 --> 01:24:39.310
and they stamped them
all over everything

01:24:39.310 --> 01:24:41.830
in a kind of enthusiastic way.

01:24:41.830 --> 01:24:43.980
So that's a problem.

01:24:43.980 --> 01:24:48.770
Also, these stamps were
made for official paper

01:24:48.770 --> 01:24:51.050
that you would write documents on.

01:24:51.050 --> 01:24:53.750
Maps were not usually
stamped with these seals,

01:24:53.750 --> 01:24:57.910
so we find that the maps have
the seals stamped all the way

01:24:57.910 --> 01:25:03.330
around the edges, and
that's not done.

01:25:03.330 --> 01:25:06.930
In looking back at the titles,
there was I think an effort here

01:25:06.930 --> 01:25:12.900 position:56%
to make them look old by making them
dirty, but smudging them with ink.

01:25:12.900 --> 01:25:16.460
So we see a lot of that
on a lot of the pages.

01:25:17.930 --> 01:25:21.290
Okay. I mentioned the
appearance, the use of Nawat.

01:25:21.290 --> 01:25:24.990
There isn't a lot in these
manuscripts and maps,

01:25:24.990 --> 01:25:30.000
but there are some examples, which
I the suggest the map makers wanted

01:25:30.000 --> 01:25:33.960
to blend an authenticity
of Nawat community,

01:25:33.960 --> 01:25:39.190
and this is their language, and,
you know, this is what they wrote,

01:25:39.190 --> 01:25:42.020
but again it's poorly done.

01:25:42.020 --> 01:25:44.760
It's by people who don't really
know the language very well,

01:25:44.760 --> 01:25:46.060
they maybe know a few words,

01:25:46.060 --> 01:25:52.290
so on this map we see it says
ninteopantzin tel tochantzin.

01:25:52.290 --> 01:25:56.270
It's their church, but
it's our town, our home.

01:25:56.270 --> 01:26:00.280
Which is a puzzling,
peculiar thing to say.

01:26:00.280 --> 01:26:03.360
There may have been some kind
of dispute in this community

01:26:03.360 --> 01:26:07.620
over whose church this was,
which town it pertained to,

01:26:07.620 --> 01:26:12.090
but that was extremely rare
and unlikely, so I don't know,

01:26:12.090 --> 01:26:14.810
whoever wrote that might not
really have realized even what they

01:26:14.810 --> 01:26:16.810
were saying.

01:26:16.810 --> 01:26:19.490
But I do want to say
that the paintings

01:26:19.490 --> 01:26:24.930
of the churches are sometimes very
realistic as though, as I said,

01:26:24.930 --> 01:26:26.250
these guys were itinerant.

01:26:26.250 --> 01:26:27.670
They went to the towns
collecting money.

01:26:27.670 --> 01:26:30.470
They also seemed to have
gone to the towns to look

01:26:30.470 --> 01:26:33.280
for legitimate local detail
to work into the maps.

01:26:33.280 --> 01:26:37.190
So the church here, the photograph
that I have is from the back,

01:26:37.190 --> 01:26:39.610
so it's not going to look
identical to you maybe,

01:26:39.610 --> 01:26:42.620
but it is the same church, so
that's kind of interesting.

01:26:42.620 --> 01:26:50.790
On a couple of the maps we have a
founding couple prostrate in front

01:26:50.790 --> 01:26:53.750
of the church, crawling toward it.

01:26:53.750 --> 01:26:55.880
And that's very unusual.

01:26:55.880 --> 01:27:00.800
I've never seen it before anywhere
else, and if you know of examples

01:27:00.800 --> 01:27:02.750
of this, I'd like to
understand the origin,

01:27:02.750 --> 01:27:06.010
where did they get this image,
and it's because it appears twice.

01:27:06.010 --> 01:27:08.000
See here's another one.

01:27:08.000 --> 01:27:10.940
Having a founding couple,
male and female,

01:27:10.940 --> 01:27:13.940
is an indigenous Mexican
characteristic

01:27:13.940 --> 01:27:17.380
of early maps and manuscripts.

01:27:17.380 --> 01:27:19.550
You know, we talk about
our founding fathers.

01:27:19.550 --> 01:27:22.870 position:56%
They had their founding mothers and
fathers, which is kind of refreshing

01:27:22.870 --> 01:27:27.970
for the gender balance, but they
very rarely crawled like, or,

01:27:27.970 --> 01:27:31.000
you know, lay down in
front of the church.

01:27:31.000 --> 01:27:36.080
This is very typical, a couple
sitting in a cave or in a building.

01:27:36.080 --> 01:27:40.890
This is the usual founding couple
arrangement, male and female, yes.

01:27:40.890 --> 01:27:42.190
And here's another one.

01:27:42.190 --> 01:27:46.150 position:56%
So these are legitimate 16th century
examples that I'm showing you

01:27:46.150 --> 01:27:49.810
of founding couples,
early ancestors and so on.

01:27:49.810 --> 01:27:52.710
That's typically the
way they appeared.

01:27:52.710 --> 01:27:55.830
Okay, also on these maps we
have these talking heads,

01:27:55.830 --> 01:28:00.820
which I showed early on,
and what I didn't say is

01:28:00.820 --> 01:28:03.820
that they have speech scrolls
coming out of their mouths,

01:28:03.820 --> 01:28:07.080
and that's an indigenous
cartographic tradition.

01:28:07.080 --> 01:28:08.450
You put people on the landscape.

01:28:08.450 --> 01:28:10.130
You put words coming
out of their mouths.

01:28:10.130 --> 01:28:13.740
The indigenous local elite was
called aglactowani [phonetic],

01:28:13.740 --> 01:28:16.860 position:56%
one who has the speech, the speaker.

01:28:16.860 --> 01:28:24.270
And in this case, this one talking
head on the upper left is saying,

01:28:24.270 --> 01:28:28.180
you know, the patron is San
Antonio, so he's speaking

01:28:28.180 --> 01:28:32.010
about the patron saint
of the local church.

01:28:32.010 --> 01:28:33.710
So that's kind of interesting.

01:28:33.710 --> 01:28:37.020
And to have large heads on
the manuscripts was something

01:28:37.020 --> 01:28:40.000
in the region known on manuscripts.

01:28:40.000 --> 01:28:43.120
I showed two examples
from the Puebla area

01:28:43.120 --> 01:28:45.450
where large heads were
put on the landscape.

01:28:45.450 --> 01:28:47.680
It's pretty unique to this region.

01:28:47.680 --> 01:28:51.230
I haven't seen it a lot in
other parts of central Mexico,

01:28:51.230 --> 01:28:56.570 position:56%
but I wondered if the map makers had
seen these other earlier manuscripts

01:28:56.570 --> 01:29:00.180
and got the idea to put
these large heads out there

01:29:00.180 --> 01:29:02.320
from these other manuscripts.

01:29:02.320 --> 01:29:03.840
And here's another example.

01:29:03.840 --> 01:29:06.900
The large head on the upper left
here, he's saying, the father,

01:29:06.900 --> 01:29:11.670 position:56%
the father, the father, which is odd
because usually it was the father,

01:29:11.670 --> 01:29:14.250
the son, the holy spirit.

01:29:14.250 --> 01:29:19.590 position:56%
And so again they've written this in
Nawat, really not sure probably how

01:29:19.590 --> 01:29:22.210
to say the father, the son,
and holy spirit in Nawat,

01:29:22.210 --> 01:29:26.720
so they just repeated the father,
which is, again, humorous for me,

01:29:26.720 --> 01:29:29.820
but I can see they were
earnestly trying here

01:29:29.820 --> 01:29:34.480
to put something believable and
authentic seeming on the landscape.

01:29:34.480 --> 01:29:37.480
I got two other examples of people.

01:29:37.480 --> 01:29:44.090
You more often would see a bust
or a whole body than just the head

01:29:44.090 --> 01:29:46.930
in many other manuscripts.

01:29:46.930 --> 01:29:48.930
So I have shown you some heads.

01:29:48.930 --> 01:29:52.570
They did exist, but this
is more common in a way.

01:29:52.570 --> 01:29:57.170
Okay, another feature from
another map example on the left,

01:29:57.170 --> 01:30:00.060
we have a comet from 1816.

01:30:00.060 --> 01:30:07.580
And I wonder if that comet was
maybe seen in the 16th Century,

01:30:07.580 --> 01:30:12.480
Duran corex [phonetic], you know,
because it has some similarities

01:30:12.480 --> 01:30:14.430
in the way it's represented,

01:30:14.430 --> 01:30:17.000
but again I really don't
know all the sources

01:30:17.000 --> 01:30:21.840
that these map makers had for
trying to infuse their maps

01:30:21.840 --> 01:30:26.050
with some authenticity and
typical indigenous traditions.

01:30:26.050 --> 01:30:29.740
There was a definite interest
in celestial phenomena,

01:30:29.740 --> 01:30:35.700
and comets were, texts are full of
references to comets, so, you know,

01:30:35.700 --> 01:30:38.050
it kind of fits in that way.

01:30:38.050 --> 01:30:43.670
One of the titles that accompanied
the maps has a reference in fact

01:30:43.670 --> 01:30:46.940
to the Aztec empire, so that's
kind of interesting again

01:30:46.940 --> 01:30:50.500
that they were thinking about,
you know, trying to reach back

01:30:50.500 --> 01:30:54.830
and connect to pre-Columbian
and early colonial times

01:30:54.830 --> 01:30:58.890
in various ways, and then
there's a reference to 1578 here,

01:30:58.890 --> 01:31:02.380
and definitely the hand
is not 16th century.

01:31:02.380 --> 01:31:05.660
One of the manuscripts has
an eagle with a serpent,

01:31:05.660 --> 01:31:09.490
and if any of you know the Mexican
flag, you know we have the eagle

01:31:09.490 --> 01:31:12.100
on a cactus with a serpent.

01:31:12.100 --> 01:31:18.380
And so again maybe they pulled
this from an earlier manuscript

01:31:18.380 --> 01:31:22.350
and put it on the map to
give that Aztec flavor.

01:31:22.350 --> 01:31:28.400
They also put serpents, and
in this case tigre, a tiger,

01:31:28.400 --> 01:31:32.740
which was really [inaudible]
the word in the Nawat

01:31:32.740 --> 01:31:36.890 position:56%
for any kind of man-eating wild cat.

01:31:36.890 --> 01:31:42.460
So you get, I really think they
mean jaguar here because serpents

01:31:42.460 --> 01:31:47.670
and jaguars were very prominent
in pre-Columbian Aztec iconography

01:31:47.670 --> 01:31:52.970
and so I also have a 16th century
map that shows a tiger on a hill,

01:31:52.970 --> 01:31:55.040
which is sort of a
glyphic representation

01:31:55.040 --> 01:31:58.940
of the word Tehuantepec,
which was wild cat hill.

01:31:58.940 --> 01:32:03.560 position:56%
And so again maybe they saw some
earlier maps, and they got the idea,

01:32:03.560 --> 01:32:07.430 position:56%
oh, let's put all over the landscape
snakes and tigers and things.

01:32:07.430 --> 01:32:12.820
So here are some other legitimately
colonial maps with snakes on them,

01:32:12.820 --> 01:32:18.210
so you can see where they
might be trying to recall that.

01:32:18.210 --> 01:32:22.490
Now this gets more like
Ripley's Believe it or Not.

01:32:22.490 --> 01:32:27.080
They have drawn and
painted in some what appear

01:32:27.080 --> 01:32:32.580
to be pre-Hispanic sculptures
in this one town in particular,

01:32:32.580 --> 01:32:35.920
and the one on the left, you know,

01:32:35.920 --> 01:32:39.480 position:56%
it does look as though maybe there's
something like this in the town,

01:32:39.480 --> 01:32:41.670
and I want to go there and
see if they have any kind

01:32:41.670 --> 01:32:43.360
of sculpture that looks like that.

01:32:43.360 --> 01:32:45.410
The one on the right
is really very strange.

01:32:45.410 --> 01:32:47.790
It looks like an alien
from outer space I think,

01:32:47.790 --> 01:32:51.630
but nothing I've seen like that.

01:32:51.630 --> 01:32:55.970
And also, you know, again like
with this mysterious Ripley's kind

01:32:55.970 --> 01:33:02.470 position:56%
of flavor, an eagle of what they say
here in the text to be 37-1/2 pounds

01:33:02.470 --> 01:33:05.720
that could life up a
sheep and carry it away.

01:33:05.720 --> 01:33:08.050
So super interesting.

01:33:08.050 --> 01:33:11.060
And here's some more
details to research locally.

01:33:11.060 --> 01:33:13.640
I haven't gone yet to
this particular town.

01:33:13.640 --> 01:33:16.040
There's so many of them,
it's going to take a while

01:33:16.040 --> 01:33:20.350
but there are a number of
really mysterious details

01:33:20.350 --> 01:33:25.430
on this Acapetlahuacan map, you
know, a man hanging by his feet.

01:33:25.430 --> 01:33:28.340
You know, a woman lying
bloody and dead.

01:33:28.340 --> 01:33:32.020
Another head suspended from
a branch and some skeletons,

01:33:32.020 --> 01:33:35.250
so this town had a really
colorful history apparently.

01:33:35.250 --> 01:33:38.720
I just really can't
wait to learn more.

01:33:38.720 --> 01:33:41.560
Now aside from trying to
reach back and bringing

01:33:41.560 --> 01:33:45.950
in indigenous traditions, these
map makers I think also tried

01:33:45.950 --> 01:33:50.370 position:56%
to infuse their maps with a
semblance of cartographic modernity.

01:33:50.370 --> 01:33:55.260
And so they have these features,
like, you know, a compass showing,

01:33:55.260 --> 01:33:56.770
you know, the cardinal points.

01:33:56.770 --> 01:33:59.460
The slightly different one

01:33:59.460 --> 01:34:02.470
to the next is again is though
there were multiple hands involved

01:34:02.470 --> 01:34:07.240
in making these maps, and
some port north on the top,

01:34:07.240 --> 01:34:09.360
and some put east on the top.

01:34:09.360 --> 01:34:11.920
So the indigenous tradition
was to put east

01:34:11.920 --> 01:34:14.180
on the top and European north.

01:34:14.180 --> 01:34:17.860
So that's something
further to research

01:34:17.860 --> 01:34:22.310
and who might have made
which type of compass.

01:34:22.310 --> 01:34:25.330
And then this example
on the right is from one

01:34:25.330 --> 01:34:28.370
of our Pueblo-Tlaxcala maps,
and it has [foreign language].

01:34:28.370 --> 01:34:36.780
I mean that's just, I've never
seen that, and it's fascinating.

01:34:36.780 --> 01:34:43.260
And that kind of language
is probably familiar to some

01:34:43.260 --> 01:34:44.620
of you who are cartographers.

01:34:44.620 --> 01:34:48.550
And on the left I can show you
that we do have some colonial maps

01:34:48.550 --> 01:34:52.510
with these kinds of
cartographic modernity beginning

01:34:52.510 --> 01:34:54.820
to appear in the 18th century.

01:34:54.820 --> 01:35:01.960 position:56%
And so it's not unusual exactly, but
it's kind of an exaggerated example.

01:35:01.960 --> 01:35:05.030
So that fascinated me.

01:35:05.030 --> 01:35:08.970 position:56%
So European influences do, you know,
creep their way into these maps.

01:35:08.970 --> 01:35:13.890
In particular, I find it in the
cartouches, in the, you know,

01:35:13.890 --> 01:35:17.350
the one on the left here,
it was incredibly elaborate,

01:35:17.350 --> 01:35:21.900
beautiful example from
a European authored map.

01:35:21.900 --> 01:35:25.190
On the right are two examples
from our Puebla-Tlaxcala group,

01:35:25.190 --> 01:35:28.540
which are, you know,
not so elaborate,

01:35:28.540 --> 01:35:32.920
especially the lower right is very
simple, but the upper right tries

01:35:32.920 --> 01:35:38.130
to be more detailed and pleasing.

01:35:38.130 --> 01:35:42.150
Okay, just to put this one example
I'm sharing with you in a context,

01:35:42.150 --> 01:35:48.870
we have known today eight title
and map manufacturing workshops

01:35:48.870 --> 01:35:53.560
in Mexican history, and so I
wanted to show you another example

01:35:53.560 --> 01:35:58.030
to give you a sense of how the
Yanez Tello group compares.

01:35:58.030 --> 01:36:01.090
Am I doing okay on time?

01:36:01.090 --> 01:36:05.050
Okay. So just a few
slides of this other group,

01:36:05.050 --> 01:36:10.720
which is led by a fellow named
Ramirez de Arellano, and these maps

01:36:10.720 --> 01:36:15.810
and titles were made
around the year 1900.

01:36:15.810 --> 01:36:17.990
Again, purporting to be colonial.

01:36:17.990 --> 01:36:21.980
In this case, almost all of them
have dates something like 1639

01:36:21.980 --> 01:36:31.890
or 1609, and so they're made on
cloth some of them and on paper.

01:36:31.890 --> 01:36:38.140
And they too have this emphasis on
the cartouche that starts out mapa,

01:36:38.140 --> 01:36:43.200
map, and so on, and they're all
indigenous towns in central Mexico.

01:36:43.200 --> 01:36:47.640
Some of these are copies, and
so the styles vary a little bit,

01:36:47.640 --> 01:36:53.270
but they're pretty similar as a
whole as you look at the group,

01:36:53.270 --> 01:36:59.080
and the legend there, map, de
las tierras map of the lands

01:36:59.080 --> 01:37:01.830
that pertain to such
and such a place.

01:37:01.830 --> 01:37:06.840
They have certain repeating
characteristics in the handwriting,

01:37:06.840 --> 01:37:08.770
the D and the E being combined,

01:37:08.770 --> 01:37:13.210
the V for U. They almost
all have a town founder,

01:37:13.210 --> 01:37:16.540
a single person on the landscape.

01:37:16.540 --> 01:37:20.070
At the center of town,
he's dressed quite the same

01:37:20.070 --> 01:37:24.710
in almost all these maps, holding
his hat down and his hand up.

01:37:24.710 --> 01:37:26.940
I think this pointing is an effort

01:37:26.940 --> 01:37:31.640 position:56%
to make him the platawane
[phonetic], the one who could speak,

01:37:31.640 --> 01:37:34.000
the local ruler, because
they often showed

01:37:34.000 --> 01:37:37.380 position:56%
in 16th century manuscripts a person

01:37:37.380 --> 01:37:41.850
with the voice also
would point the finger.

01:37:41.850 --> 01:37:45.610
So I think that's what's
happening here.

01:37:45.610 --> 01:37:50.510
Interestingly, in 2009 the town,
