01:39:19.040 --> 01:39:24.880
and they tried to use that
method for replicating rivers.

01:39:24.880 --> 01:39:31.580 position:56%
Okay, so to summarize and figure out
what our takeaways are from looking

01:39:31.580 --> 01:39:37.210
at these kinds of mass-produced
maps and manuscripts.

01:39:37.210 --> 01:39:40.960
I want to urge that we not
dismiss them outright as forgery,

01:39:40.960 --> 01:39:43.230 position:56%
so we're looking at fact or fiction.

01:39:43.230 --> 01:39:46.320
For me it's fact and fiction.

01:39:46.320 --> 01:39:49.880
It's more fitting to say
that these are contrived.

01:39:49.880 --> 01:39:54.100
In other words, they've taken
local input to make a vision

01:39:54.100 --> 01:39:58.730
of a community that fit what the
town itself might recognize even

01:39:58.730 --> 01:40:03.950
if they've also tried to pretend
it's early, old, which would,

01:40:03.950 --> 01:40:07.300
if it ended up in the courts
perhaps help the community defend

01:40:07.300 --> 01:40:09.350
their lands.

01:40:09.350 --> 01:40:12.470
Towns desperately need a
documentation, so they were ready

01:40:12.470 --> 01:40:17.960
to pay these exorbitant prices
to get maps for their towns,

01:40:17.960 --> 01:40:20.860
to fulfill that need
to defend their towns.

01:40:20.860 --> 01:40:23.220
And it wasn't such a
level playing field.

01:40:23.220 --> 01:40:27.140
In the colonial period and
especially in the 19th century,

01:40:27.140 --> 01:40:30.040
there were a number of laws
attacking group-held lands,

01:40:30.040 --> 01:40:34.390
and indigenous community
lands were held by the town.

01:40:34.390 --> 01:40:36.590
Use of parcels was individualized,

01:40:36.590 --> 01:40:38.870
but as a whole land
was held by the group.

01:40:38.870 --> 01:40:42.050
So in the reforms of the
second half of the 19th century

01:40:42.050 --> 01:40:45.570
that attacked group held
lands, which were mainly aimed

01:40:45.570 --> 01:40:49.750
at the Catholic church, they
affected indigenous communities.

01:40:49.750 --> 01:40:53.030
Then Maximillian of Hapsburg
came in and reversed that,

01:40:53.030 --> 01:40:56.010
but then we had a dictatorship,
Porfirio Diaz [phonetic],

01:40:56.010 --> 01:40:59.590
in the late 19th century
Mexico, where he returned

01:40:59.590 --> 01:41:04.980 position:56%
to attack a group-held land, and it
was when it was in that last quarter

01:41:04.980 --> 01:41:07.110
of the 19th century, last
third of the 19th century

01:41:07.110 --> 01:41:11.350
when indigenous lands were really
alienated more than ever before

01:41:11.350 --> 01:41:15.430
and large estates were being
built up more than ever before.

01:41:15.430 --> 01:41:19.640
So it was tough, and towns were
really desparate for some documents

01:41:19.640 --> 01:41:21.750
to defend their communities.

01:41:21.750 --> 01:41:26.760
So I call that the, you know, the
social versus the legal context,

01:41:26.760 --> 01:41:29.470
and as I said, there were
eight such workshops,

01:41:29.470 --> 01:41:32.590
so this is a huge phenomenon.

01:41:32.590 --> 01:41:37.480
There was a recent book by Karina
Olds called "Forging the Past"

01:41:37.480 --> 01:41:41.390
in which she looks at medieval
and Renaissance manuscripts

01:41:41.390 --> 01:41:45.500
to understand some of the
complexities of forgery,

01:41:45.500 --> 01:41:50.150
and one quote I just thought
I would share with you here

01:41:50.150 --> 01:41:54.990
from her recent book
is forgeries were not,

01:41:54.990 --> 01:41:58.700
at least from the perspective of
their perpetrators, outright lies.

01:41:58.700 --> 01:42:03.000
They were rather a recovery of
a deeper, more essential truth,

01:42:03.000 --> 01:42:07.620 position:56%
that had been waylaid somehow, or in
the case of indigenous communities,

01:42:07.620 --> 01:42:11.910
maybe they never had documents
to defend their territories.

01:42:11.910 --> 01:42:18.210
And yet I don't want to be
speculative or not enough,

01:42:18.210 --> 01:42:21.970
I want to say that science is
also important, and so we need

01:42:21.970 --> 01:42:25.070
to take science to our
study of these manuscripts.

01:42:25.070 --> 01:42:31.140
We have to have a methodology
that allows us to recognize

01:42:31.140 --> 01:42:34.160
when a new map or manuscript
emerges.

01:42:34.160 --> 01:42:36.330
Does it fit in some of
these known corpuses?

01:42:36.330 --> 01:42:41.230
Does it have that kind of
style, that orthography,

01:42:41.230 --> 01:42:44.280
terminology, handwriting.

01:42:45.530 --> 01:42:49.350
We even need to look more at the
paper or the cloth and so on,

01:42:49.350 --> 01:42:52.900
and we need to seat the historical
context that produced the map

01:42:52.900 --> 01:42:55.620
and also the history
that it conveys.

01:42:55.620 --> 01:42:57.450
We don't want to undermine
their validity

01:42:57.450 --> 01:43:01.400
for the indigenous communities,
but we can't be naïve either,

01:43:01.400 --> 01:43:04.230
so we have both fact and fiction.

