01:53:59.040 --> 01:54:02.840
&gt;&gt; A question for Kirsten Seaver,
could you expand a little bit more

01:54:02.840 --> 01:54:06.880
on your description of
Father Fischer's relationship

01:54:06.880 --> 01:54:12.550
to the Vinland map and what motive
he might have to commit a forgery

01:54:12.550 --> 01:54:19.400
and why a researcher of his stature
would do something like that?

01:54:19.400 --> 01:54:24.740
&gt;&gt; Kirsten Seaver: You mean what
propelled me to research it or?

01:54:24.740 --> 01:54:27.780
&gt;&gt; No, I thought at the end
of your talk you implied

01:54:27.780 --> 01:54:31.530
that Father Fischer was the
creator of the Vinland map.

01:54:31.530 --> 01:54:32.830
&gt;&gt; Kirsten Seaver: Yes, uh-huh.

01:54:32.830 --> 01:54:35.100
&gt;&gt; And what was his motive?

01:54:35.100 --> 01:54:38.660
What do you think his motive
might be and why would

01:54:38.660 --> 01:54:46.620
such a professional researcher like
Father Fischer commit that forgery?

01:54:46.620 --> 01:54:50.550
&gt;&gt; Kirsten Seaver:
It's very difficult

01:54:50.550 --> 01:54:55.400 position:56%
to explain Father Fischer's
personality unless you have read all

01:54:55.400 --> 01:55:01.600
his writings, but essentially he
was an extremely Arodite [phonetic]

01:55:01.600 --> 01:55:06.420
and at the same time naive
person, and he had a kind

01:55:06.420 --> 01:55:09.290
of a fixed framework of thinking.

01:55:09.290 --> 01:55:13.560
Once he had hit upon an idea
an become convinced about it,

01:55:13.560 --> 01:55:19.000
such as that the Norse had
left a cartographic trail,

01:55:19.000 --> 01:55:24.260
there was no budging him,
really no budging him.

01:55:24.260 --> 01:55:35.040
And so in his old age, he was in
a situation where he had retired.

01:55:35.040 --> 01:55:40.990
The Nazis had taken over Austria
and of course Germany first.

01:55:40.990 --> 01:55:46.490
They were persecuting Catholic
priests, which is what he was,

01:55:46.490 --> 01:55:53.100
which is why he was given refuge
at Wolfegg, and they were trampling

01:55:53.100 --> 01:55:56.250
on some of the things that
were dearest to his heart,

01:55:56.250 --> 01:56:02.470
and that was the truth of
cartographic history and the Norse.

01:56:02.470 --> 01:56:08.870
I mean he knew that the Norse
were the Norse from the far north.

01:56:08.870 --> 01:56:10.830
That had nothing to
do with what was going

01:56:10.830 --> 01:56:13.140 position:56%
on in the so-called greater Germany.

01:56:13.140 --> 01:56:17.450
He was an educated
cartographic historian.

01:56:17.450 --> 01:56:22.770
Then in the mid-1930's, he
had completed his magna opus

01:56:22.770 --> 01:56:30.620 position:56%
on the Ptolemaic maps in the Vatican
library, early Ptolemaic maps,

01:56:30.620 --> 01:56:34.120
and the book was reviewed
by Leo Bogrov [phonetic],

01:56:34.120 --> 01:56:39.510
who didn't like it at all, and
Fischer was absolutely crushed.

01:56:39.510 --> 01:56:44.130
This was the low point in his
life, with the Nazis without

01:56:44.130 --> 01:56:47.310
and then Leo Bogrov's
review in front of him.

01:56:47.310 --> 01:56:55.470
And he got ahold of an old
manuscript that he could use,

01:56:55.470 --> 01:57:03.880
and he made in his quiet moments
of his life, he made a map,

01:57:03.880 --> 01:57:09.600
which he was convinced at one
time actually existed in one form.

01:57:09.600 --> 01:57:13.170
He never made it for sale.

01:57:13.170 --> 01:57:17.350
He had no personal property
as a Jesuit, so at some point

01:57:17.350 --> 01:57:20.350
when he died it would
have floated out there,

01:57:20.350 --> 01:57:22.560
and he was sure the Nazis
would have had to pick it

01:57:22.560 --> 01:57:28.220
over in their own peculiar
fashion, and he put in this riddle.

01:57:29.430 --> 01:57:32.770
As I said, he would have been
appalled had he known what happened

01:57:32.770 --> 01:57:34.200
to it afterwards.

01:57:34.200 --> 01:57:37.790
He was a very strange man.

01:57:37.790 --> 01:57:40.610
The Vinland map is a
very strange production.

01:57:40.610 --> 01:57:45.510
It is a product of his
old and unhappy life.

