01:58:08.180 --> 01:58:12.780
&gt;&gt; For Stephanie, this
series of maps is really part

01:58:12.780 --> 01:58:16.810
of an old tradition of forgery
in Mexico and other places

01:58:16.810 --> 01:58:20.240
to support indigenous land claims.

01:58:20.240 --> 01:58:23.070
Maybe you could talk a little
bit about that tradition and also

01:58:23.070 --> 01:58:30.800
about the type of social cohesion
in a community that would coalesce

01:58:30.800 --> 01:58:38.720
to pay for, hide, and contribute to
the manufacture of this vast amount

01:58:38.720 --> 01:58:44.780 position:56%
of information and kind of one would
imagine in secret, I mean in secret

01:58:44.780 --> 01:58:48.940
from the Mexican authorities
or the [inaudible].

01:58:48.940 --> 01:58:52.950
&gt;&gt; Stephanie Wood:
Yeah, thanks Arthur.

01:58:52.950 --> 01:58:55.860
Good to see you again.

01:58:55.860 --> 01:59:00.340
Yeah, with eight workshops we've
now identified producing maps

01:59:00.340 --> 01:59:04.080 position:56%
and manuscripts to defend indigenous
communities we know is a massive

01:59:04.080 --> 01:59:10.060
tradition, and we're trying to
understand each group is unique

01:59:10.060 --> 01:59:12.780 position:56%
in itself in its approach and so on,

01:59:12.780 --> 01:59:18.070 position:56%
but we have for instance
primordial titles as they're called,

01:59:18.070 --> 01:59:22.540
which are written in indigenous
languages or which really try hard

01:59:22.540 --> 01:59:26.450
to suggest they came internally
from the communities involved,

01:59:26.450 --> 01:59:29.360
and yet because now
we've identified so many

01:59:29.360 --> 01:59:32.140
of them we can see they
have recurring elements

01:59:32.140 --> 01:59:35.760
that suggest mass production,
and yet, again,

01:59:35.760 --> 01:59:40.980
a real effort to include local
detail, and the social cohesion

01:59:40.980 --> 01:59:43.850
in terms of acquiring
these kinds of things

01:59:43.850 --> 01:59:45.730
that people would come together.

01:59:45.730 --> 01:59:50.630
It was the leadership was
really a crucial element there.

01:59:50.630 --> 01:59:55.430
Leaders had sometimes benefited
personally from the stories

01:59:55.430 --> 01:59:58.500
that were told because their
ancestors would be featured.

01:59:58.500 --> 02:00:05.470
Some titles include testaments of
town leaders, ancestors, and so on,

02:00:05.470 --> 02:00:09.880
so they would urge the community,
you know, this is really important,

02:00:09.880 --> 02:00:12.750
we need this, we need to
raise funds to buy this,

02:00:12.750 --> 02:00:16.400
and they were often doing that
for other purposes too, you know,

02:00:16.400 --> 02:00:20.590
for religious festivals, so in the
Puebla-Tlaxcala area for instance,

02:00:20.590 --> 02:00:24.360
it was the fescales, the
indigenous community leaders,

02:00:24.360 --> 02:00:27.010
who were associated with the
church, who were doing a lot

02:00:27.010 --> 02:00:31.050
of the fundraising I think for
buying these kinds of things.

02:00:31.050 --> 02:00:36.660
And you can just see
it in the way the town,

02:00:36.660 --> 02:00:41.070
the towns still do embrace these
even though they very often can't

02:00:41.070 --> 02:00:44.500
read them anymore, and they don't
even really know what they say.

02:00:44.500 --> 02:00:46.830
There might be one or two people
who can read them and explain

02:00:46.830 --> 02:00:49.390
to the town, so I went
to [inaudible],

02:00:49.390 --> 02:00:54.020
which had that 400th anniversary
of the validity of our manuscript.

02:00:54.020 --> 02:00:57.100
I went, every couple
years they handed

02:00:57.100 --> 02:00:59.780
from one town manuscript
guardian to the next,

02:00:59.780 --> 02:01:02.700
and they have a big ceremony,
and they have a princess.

02:01:02.700 --> 02:01:07.070
And they have a long
recitation they read in Nawat

02:01:07.070 --> 02:01:09.760
that most people don't
understand it anymore.

02:01:09.760 --> 02:01:13.030
And they get out, they
truck out their lienzo,

02:01:13.030 --> 02:01:14.470
and everybody walks around it.

02:01:14.470 --> 02:01:17.280
And they want the youth
to see it and know it,

02:01:17.280 --> 02:01:19.650
and this is our town,
and this is our charter.

02:01:19.650 --> 02:01:20.950
And this is really important to us,

02:01:20.950 --> 02:01:25.730
and so everybody nods
and goes along with it.

02:01:25.730 --> 02:01:27.750
Anyway, and they also reject.

02:01:27.750 --> 02:01:31.870
They don't want to hear any of
the scientific analysis of it.

02:01:31.870 --> 02:01:35.860
So am sympathetic, I
really am toward them,

02:01:35.860 --> 02:01:38.680
but then I also, it's awkward.

02:01:38.680 --> 02:01:40.370
I'm not quite sure
how to deal with that.

02:01:40.370 --> 02:01:44.020
I have a book on this that I've
been developing for a long time

02:01:44.020 --> 02:01:46.070
because there are so many
different interesting groups,

02:01:46.070 --> 02:01:48.200
and they have such
interesting stories.

02:01:48.200 --> 02:01:53.100
But I've been worried that
people will see it as an attack

02:01:53.100 --> 02:01:57.500 position:56%
on indigenous community landholding,
which I don't feel it's an attack.

02:01:57.500 --> 02:02:00.130
I mean some communities
will say we're very glad

02:02:00.130 --> 02:02:01.870
to know what you have
to tell us here.

02:02:01.870 --> 02:02:03.990
We don't want to be
naive either, you know,

02:02:03.990 --> 02:02:05.290
so we want to know what this is.

02:02:05.290 --> 02:02:08.650
Even if we like it, we
want to know it's origin.

02:02:08.650 --> 02:02:11.040
So that's a complicated,
roundabout answer.

02:02:11.040 --> 02:02:13.840
I hope I got to what
you were looking for.

